WEBVTT

1
00:00:14.973 --> 00:00:17.851
(wind whistling)

2
00:00:28.153 --> 00:00:32.323
(wind howling)

3
00:01:03.354 --> 00:01:06.316
(birds chirping)

4
00:01:11.029 --> 00:01:14.908
(chirping continues)

5
00:01:47.816 --> 00:01:52.278
(church bell tolling)

6
00:02:43.204 --> 00:02:46.332
<i>♪ The hills are alive ♪</i>

7
00:02:46.416 --> 00:02:51.045
<i>♪ With the sound of music ♪</i>

8
00:02:51.129 --> 00:02:53.673
<i>♪ With songs they have sung ♪</i>

9
00:02:53.756 --> 00:02:58.761
<i>♪ For a thousand years ♪</i>

10
00:02:58.845 --> 00:03:02.182
<i>♪ The hills fill my heart ♪</i>

11
00:03:02.265 --> 00:03:06.936
<i>♪ With the sound of music ♪</i>

12
00:03:07.020 --> 00:03:08.938
<i>♪ My heart wants to sing ♪</i>

13
00:03:09.022 --> 00:03:14.027
<i>♪ Every song it hears ♪</i>

14
00:03:14.110 --> 00:03:16.905
<i>♪ My heart wants to beat ♪</i>

15
00:03:16.988 --> 00:03:19.657
<i>♪ Like the wings of the birds that rise ♪</i>

16
00:03:19.741 --> 00:03:23.369
<i>♪ From the lake to the trees ♪</i>

17
00:03:23.453 --> 00:03:27.457
<i>♪ My heart wants to sigh</i>
<i>like a chime that flies ♪</i>

18
00:03:27.540 --> 00:03:31.753
<i>♪ From a church on a breeze ♪</i>

19
00:03:31.836 --> 00:03:35.590
<i>♪ To laugh like a brook</i>
<i>when it trips and falls ♪</i>

20
00:03:35.673 --> 00:03:39.385
<i>♪ Over stones on its way ♪</i>

21
00:03:39.469 --> 00:03:43.306
<i>♪ To sing through the night ♪</i>

22
00:03:43.389 --> 00:03:47.185
<i>♪ Like a lark who is learning to pray ♪</i>

23
00:03:47.268 --> 00:03:53.358
<i>♪ I go to the hills ♪</i>

24
00:03:53.441 --> 00:03:58.238
<i>♪ When my heart is lonely ♪</i>

25
00:03:59.948 --> 00:04:03.284
<i>♪ I know I will hear ♪</i>

26
00:04:03.368 --> 00:04:08.873
<i>♪ What I've heard before ♪</i>

27
00:04:08.957 --> 00:04:13.294
<i>♪ My heart will be blessed ♪</i>

28
00:04:13.378 --> 00:04:20.426
<i>♪ With the sound of music ♪</i>

29
00:04:22.512 --> 00:04:27.725
<i>♪ And I'll sing ♪</i>

30
00:04:27.809 --> 00:04:31.104
<i>♪ Once ♪</i>

31
00:04:31.187 --> 00:04:36.359
<i>♪ More ♪</i>

32
00:04:38.695 --> 00:04:42.156
(church bells tolling)

33
00:04:45.368 --> 00:04:49.664
(tolling continues)

34
00:04:52.583 --> 00:04:54.335
Oh!

35
00:04:54.419 --> 00:04:55.420
(music playing)

36
00:07:33.119 --> 00:07:38.958
(female choir singing in Latin)

37
00:09:09.799 --> 00:09:14.554
(chapel bell tolling)

38
00:09:18.474 --> 00:09:23.521
<i>♪ Alleluia, alleluia ♪</i>

39
00:09:23.604 --> 00:09:26.274
<i>♪ Alleluia ♪</i>

40
00:09:26.357 --> 00:09:28.568
(singing continues)

41
00:09:30.903 --> 00:09:33.155
-Reverend Mother.
-Sister Bernice.

42
00:09:33.239 --> 00:09:35.992
-I simply cannot find her.
-Maria?

43
00:09:36.867 --> 00:09:38.411
She's missing from the abbey again.

44
00:09:39.287 --> 00:09:41.789
Perhaps we should have put
a cowbell around her neck.

45
00:09:41.872 --> 00:09:42.957
Have you tried the barn?

46
00:09:43.040 --> 00:09:44.917
You know how much
she adores the animals.

47
00:09:45.001 --> 00:09:47.920
I have looked everywhere,
in all of the usual places.

48
00:09:48.004 --> 00:09:50.673
Sister Bernice,
considering that it's Maria,

49
00:09:50.756 --> 00:09:53.384
I suggest you look
in someplace unusual.

50
00:09:58.556 --> 00:10:01.851
Well, Reverend Mother,
I hope this new infraction

51
00:10:01.934 --> 00:10:06.063
ends whatever doubts you may
still have about Maria's future here.

52
00:10:06.147 --> 00:10:10.484
I always try to keep faith
in my doubts, Sister Berthe.

53
00:10:10.568 --> 00:10:13.738
After all, the wool of a black sheep
is just as warm.

54
00:10:13.821 --> 00:10:18.451
We are not talking about sheep,
black or white, Sister Margaretta.

55
00:10:18.534 --> 00:10:20.536
Of all the candidates
for the novitiate,

56
00:10:20.620 --> 00:10:23.914
-I would say Maria is the least likely--
-Children, children!

57
00:10:24.832 --> 00:10:29.003
We were speculating about the
qualifications of some of our postulants.

58
00:10:29.086 --> 00:10:32.632
The mistress of novices
and the mistress of postulants

59
00:10:32.715 --> 00:10:38.304
were trying to help me
by expressing opposite points of view.

60
00:10:38.387 --> 00:10:41.515
Tell me, Sister Catherine,
what do you think of... Maria?

61
00:10:41.599 --> 00:10:44.810
She's a wonderful girl, some of the time.

62
00:10:45.895 --> 00:10:49.190
-Sister Agatha?
-It's very easy to like Maria,

63
00:10:49.273 --> 00:10:51.692
except when it's, uh, difficult.

64
00:10:51.776 --> 00:10:53.402
And you, Sister Sophia?

65
00:10:53.486 --> 00:10:55.404
I love her very dearly,

66
00:10:55.488 --> 00:10:58.949
but she always seems to be
in trouble, doesn't she?

67
00:10:59.033 --> 00:11:01.077
Exactly what I say.

68
00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:03.454
<i>♪ She climbs a tree</i>
<i>and scrapes her knee ♪</i>

69
00:11:03.537 --> 00:11:05.289
<i>♪ Her dress has got a tear ♪</i>

70
00:11:05.373 --> 00:11:08.417
<i>♪ She waltzes on her way to mass ♪</i>

71
00:11:08.501 --> 00:11:10.795
<i>♪ And whistles on the stair ♪</i>

72
00:11:10.878 --> 00:11:12.963
<i>♪ And underneath her wimple ♪</i>

73
00:11:13.047 --> 00:11:15.257
<i>♪ She has curlers in her hair ♪</i>

74
00:11:15.341 --> 00:11:20.179
<i>♪ I've even heard her</i>
<i>singing in the abbey ♪</i>

75
00:11:20.262 --> 00:11:22.431
<i>♪ She's always late for chapel ♪</i>

76
00:11:22.515 --> 00:11:24.892
<i>♪ But her penitence is real ♪</i>

77
00:11:24.975 --> 00:11:27.520
<i>♪ She's always late for everything ♪</i>

78
00:11:27.603 --> 00:11:29.772
<i>♪ Except for every meal ♪</i>

79
00:11:29.855 --> 00:11:32.400
<i>♪ I hate to have to say it ♪</i>

80
00:11:32.483 --> 00:11:34.819
<i>♪ But I very firmly feel ♪</i>

81
00:11:34.902 --> 00:11:39.490
<i>♪ Maria's not an asset to the abbey ♪</i>

82
00:11:39.573 --> 00:11:42.827
<i>♪ I'd like to say a word in her behalf ♪</i>

83
00:11:42.910 --> 00:11:45.204
Then say it, Sister Margaretta.

84
00:11:45.287 --> 00:11:48.916
<i>♪ Maria makes me laugh ♪</i>

85
00:11:48.999 --> 00:11:52.002
(laughter)

86
00:11:52.086 --> 00:11:55.715
<i>♪ How do you solve a problem like Maria ♪</i>

87
00:11:55.798 --> 00:11:59.677
<i>♪ How do you catch a cloud</i>
<i>and pin it down ♪</i>

88
00:11:59.760 --> 00:12:03.472
<i>♪ How do you find a word</i>
<i>that means Maria ♪</i>

89
00:12:03.556 --> 00:12:04.807
<i>♪ A flibbertigibbet ♪</i>

90
00:12:04.890 --> 00:12:07.601
<i>-♪ A will-o'-the-wisp ♪</i>
<i>-♪ A clown ♪</i>

91
00:12:08.436 --> 00:12:11.814
<i>♪ Many a thing you know</i>
<i>you'd like to tell her ♪</i>

92
00:12:11.897 --> 00:12:15.735
<i>♪ Many a thing</i>
<i>she ought to understand ♪</i>

93
00:12:15.818 --> 00:12:18.070
<i>♪ But how do you make her stay ♪</i>

94
00:12:18.154 --> 00:12:19.864
<i>♪ And listen to all you say ♪</i>

95
00:12:19.947 --> 00:12:23.909
<i>♪ How do you keep</i>
<i>a wave upon the sand ♪</i>

96
00:12:23.993 --> 00:12:28.205
<i>♪ Oh, how do you solve</i>
<i>a problem like Maria ♪</i>

97
00:12:28.289 --> 00:12:34.712
<i>♪ How do you hold a moonbeam ♪</i>

98
00:12:34.795 --> 00:12:39.592
<i>♪ In your hand ♪</i>

99
00:12:41.093 --> 00:12:42.803
<i>♪ When I'm with her I'm confused ♪</i>

100
00:12:42.887 --> 00:12:44.805
<i>♪ Out of focus and bemused ♪</i>

101
00:12:44.889 --> 00:12:48.517
<i>♪ And I never know exactly where I am ♪</i>

102
00:12:48.601 --> 00:12:50.352
<i>♪ Unpredictable as weather ♪</i>

103
00:12:50.436 --> 00:12:52.188
<i>♪ She's as flighty as a feather ♪</i>

104
00:12:52.271 --> 00:12:54.023
<i>-♪ She's a darling ♪</i>
<i>-♪ She's a demon ♪</i>

105
00:12:54.106 --> 00:12:55.608
<i>♪ She's a lamb ♪</i>

106
00:12:55.691 --> 00:12:58.027
<i>♪ She'd out-pester any pest ♪</i>

107
00:12:58.110 --> 00:12:59.987
<i>♪ Drive a hornet from its nest ♪</i>

108
00:13:00.070 --> 00:13:03.115
<i>♪ She can throw a whirling dervish</i>
<i>out of whirl ♪</i>

109
00:13:03.199 --> 00:13:05.493
<i>♪ She is gentle, she is wild ♪</i>

110
00:13:05.576 --> 00:13:07.661
<i>♪ She's a riddle, she's a child ♪</i>

111
00:13:07.745 --> 00:13:10.414
<i>-♪ She's a headache ♪</i>
<i>-♪ She's an angel ♪</i>

112
00:13:10.498 --> 00:13:14.960
<i>♪ She's a girl ♪</i>

113
00:13:15.044 --> 00:13:19.215
<i>♪ How do you solve a problem like Maria ♪</i>

114
00:13:19.298 --> 00:13:23.135
<i>♪ How do you catch a cloud</i>
<i>and pin it down ♪</i>

115
00:13:23.219 --> 00:13:26.639
<i>♪ How do you find a word</i>
<i>that means Maria ♪</i>

116
00:13:26.722 --> 00:13:28.349
<i>♪ A flibbertigibbet ♪</i>

117
00:13:28.432 --> 00:13:31.727
<i>-♪ A will-o'-the-wisp ♪</i>
<i>-♪ A clown ♪</i>

118
00:13:31.811 --> 00:13:35.356
<i>♪ Many a thing you know</i>
<i>you'd like to tell her ♪</i>

119
00:13:35.439 --> 00:13:39.360
<i>♪ Many a thing she ought to understand ♪</i>

120
00:13:39.443 --> 00:13:41.362
<i>♪ But how do you make her stay ♪</i>

121
00:13:41.445 --> 00:13:43.697
<i>♪ And listen to all you say ♪</i>

122
00:13:43.781 --> 00:13:47.868
<i>♪ How do you keep</i>
<i>a wave upon the sand ♪</i>

123
00:13:47.952 --> 00:13:53.249
<i>♪ Oh, how do you solve</i>
<i>a problem like Maria ♪</i>

124
00:13:53.332 --> 00:13:55.042
(door slams)

125
00:14:10.182 --> 00:14:17.106
<i>♪ How do you hold a moonbeam ♪</i>

126
00:14:17.189 --> 00:14:23.821
<i>♪ In your hand ♪</i>

127
00:14:35.291 --> 00:14:37.293
You may go in now, Maria.

128
00:14:50.264 --> 00:14:51.390
Come here, my child.

129
00:14:58.272 --> 00:15:00.441
-Now, sit down.
-Oh!

130
00:15:00.524 --> 00:15:02.651
Oh, Reverend Mother, I'm so sorry.

131
00:15:02.735 --> 00:15:04.570
I just couldn't help myself.

132
00:15:04.653 --> 00:15:06.906
The gates were open, and the hills
were beckoning, and before I--

133
00:15:06.989 --> 00:15:09.950
Maria, I haven't summoned
you here for apologies.

134
00:15:10.034 --> 00:15:12.411
Oh, please, Mother,
do let me ask for forgiveness.

135
00:15:12.494 --> 00:15:14.413
If it would make you feel better.

136
00:15:15.456 --> 00:15:17.917
Yes. Well, you see,
the sky was so blue today,

137
00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:19.835
and everything was
so green and fragrant.

138
00:15:19.919 --> 00:15:21.795
I just had to be a part of it.

139
00:15:21.879 --> 00:15:24.340
And the Untersberg kept
leading me higher and higher,

140
00:15:24.423 --> 00:15:26.425
as though it wanted me to go
right through the clouds with it.

141
00:15:26.508 --> 00:15:28.761
But child, suppose darkness
had come and you were lost?

142
00:15:28.844 --> 00:15:31.513
Oh, Mother, I could never
be lost up there.

143
00:15:31.597 --> 00:15:34.141
That's my mountain.
I was brought up on it.

144
00:15:34.224 --> 00:15:37.353
-It was the mountain that led me to you.
- Oh?

145
00:15:37.436 --> 00:15:39.647
When I was a child,
I would come down the mountain

146
00:15:39.730 --> 00:15:42.816
and climb a tree and look over
into your garden.

147
00:15:42.900 --> 00:15:45.819
I'd see the sisters at work, and I'd
hear them sing on their way to vespers.

148
00:15:47.196 --> 00:15:50.699
Which brings me to another transgression,
Reverend Mother.

149
00:15:50.783 --> 00:15:53.077
I was singing out there today
without permission.

150
00:15:53.160 --> 00:15:57.748
Maria, it is only here in the abbey that
we have rules about postulants singing.

151
00:15:57.831 --> 00:16:00.376
I can't seem to stop singing
wherever I am.

152
00:16:00.459 --> 00:16:02.753
And what's worse,
I can't seem to stop saying things--

153
00:16:02.836 --> 00:16:05.214
everything and anything I think and feel.

154
00:16:05.297 --> 00:16:06.799
Some people would call that honesty.

155
00:16:06.882 --> 00:16:08.717
Oh, but it's terrible, Reverend Mother.

156
00:16:09.677 --> 00:16:11.679
You know how Sister Berthe
always makes me kiss the floor

157
00:16:11.762 --> 00:16:13.681
after we've had a disagreement?

158
00:16:13.764 --> 00:16:15.349
Well, lately I've taken
to kissing the floor

159
00:16:15.432 --> 00:16:17.267
when I see her coming just to save time.

160
00:16:20.187 --> 00:16:23.857
Maria, when you saw us
over the abbey wall

161
00:16:23.941 --> 00:16:27.945
and longed to be one of us,
that didn't necessarily mean

162
00:16:28.028 --> 00:16:30.239
that you were prepared
for the way we live here, did it?

163
00:16:31.657 --> 00:16:34.034
No, Mother,
but I-- I pray, and I try,

164
00:16:34.118 --> 00:16:36.245
and I am learning, I really am.

165
00:16:36.328 --> 00:16:38.747
And what is the most important
lesson you have learned here, my child?

166
00:16:38.831 --> 00:16:43.293
To find out what is the will of God
and to do it wholeheartedly.

167
00:16:45.921 --> 00:16:47.047
Maria...

168
00:16:48.632 --> 00:16:51.635
It seems to be the will
of God that you leave us.

169
00:16:51.719 --> 00:16:53.846
-Leave?
-Only for a while, Maria.

170
00:16:53.929 --> 00:16:56.098
Oh, no, Mother, please don't do that.
Don't send me away.

171
00:16:56.181 --> 00:16:59.476
This is where I belong.
It's my home, my family.

172
00:16:59.560 --> 00:17:02.479
-It's my life.
-But are you truly ready for it?

173
00:17:02.563 --> 00:17:04.273
Yes, I am.

174
00:17:04.356 --> 00:17:07.234
Perhaps if you go out
into the world for a time,

175
00:17:07.317 --> 00:17:09.486
knowing what we expect of you,

176
00:17:09.570 --> 00:17:12.364
you will have a chance to find out
if you can expect it of yourself.

177
00:17:12.448 --> 00:17:14.450
I know what you expect, Mother,
and I can do it.

178
00:17:14.533 --> 00:17:16.952
-I promise I can.
-Maria.

179
00:17:20.622 --> 00:17:21.749
Yes, Mother.

180
00:17:23.751 --> 00:17:25.335
If it is God's will.

181
00:17:27.629 --> 00:17:30.466
There is a family near Salzburg

182
00:17:30.549 --> 00:17:33.135
that needs a governess until September.

183
00:17:33.218 --> 00:17:35.262
-Until September?
-To take care of seven children.

184
00:17:35.345 --> 00:17:38.432
-Seven children!
-Do you like children, Maria?

185
00:17:38.515 --> 00:17:41.101
Well, yes, but seven!

186
00:17:42.102 --> 00:17:45.355
I will tell Captain von Trapp
to expect you tomorrow.

187
00:17:45.439 --> 00:17:47.316
Uh, Captain?

188
00:17:48.650 --> 00:17:50.569
A retired officer of the Imperial Navy.

189
00:17:50.652 --> 00:17:52.279
A fine man and a brave one.

190
00:17:53.238 --> 00:17:55.741
His wife died several years ago,
leaving him alone with the children.

191
00:17:55.824 --> 00:17:59.578
I understand he's had a most difficult
time managing to keep a governess there.

192
00:18:01.163 --> 00:18:03.415
Uh, why difficult,
Reverend Mother?

193
00:18:04.917 --> 00:18:07.586
The Lord will show you
in his own good time.

194
00:18:10.297 --> 00:18:13.967
(female choir singing in Latin)

195
00:18:44.706 --> 00:18:49.169
When the Lord closes a door,
somewhere he opens a window.

196
00:18:52.172 --> 00:18:56.552
<i>♪ What will this day be like ♪</i>

197
00:18:57.553 --> 00:18:59.555
<i>♪ I wonder ♪</i>

198
00:19:06.228 --> 00:19:10.149
<i>♪ What will my future be ♪</i>

199
00:19:11.191 --> 00:19:13.277
<i>♪ I wonder ♪</i>

200
00:19:14.987 --> 00:19:18.031
<i>♪ It could be so exciting ♪</i>

201
00:19:18.115 --> 00:19:21.243
<i>♪ To be out in the world</i>
<i>To be free ♪</i>

202
00:19:21.326 --> 00:19:24.538
<i>♪ My heart should be</i>
<i>wildly rejoicing ♪</i>

203
00:19:25.706 --> 00:19:31.086
<i>♪ Oh, what's the matter with me ♪</i>

204
00:19:31.170 --> 00:19:34.631
<i>♪ I have always longed for adventure ♪</i>

205
00:19:34.715 --> 00:19:38.385
<i>♪ To do the things I've never dared ♪</i>

206
00:19:38.468 --> 00:19:41.889
<i>♪ Now here I'm facing adventure ♪</i>

207
00:19:41.972 --> 00:19:44.099
<i>♪ Then why ♪</i>

208
00:19:44.183 --> 00:19:48.562
<i>♪ Am I so scared ♪</i>

209
00:19:51.648 --> 00:19:54.568
<i>♪ A captain with seven children ♪</i>

210
00:19:54.651 --> 00:19:56.987
<i>♪ What's so fearsome about that ♪</i>

211
00:19:59.156 --> 00:20:02.701
<i>♪ Oh, I must stop these doubts</i>
<i>all these worries ♪</i>

212
00:20:02.784 --> 00:20:05.871
<i>♪ If I don't I just know I'll turn back ♪</i>

213
00:20:05.954 --> 00:20:08.874
<i>♪ I must dream of the things</i>
<i>I am seeking ♪</i>

214
00:20:10.083 --> 00:20:15.964
<i>♪ I am seeking the courage I lack ♪</i>

215
00:20:16.048 --> 00:20:20.010
<i>♪ The courage to serve them</i>
<i>with reliance ♪</i>

216
00:20:20.093 --> 00:20:23.055
<i>♪ Face my mistakes without defiance ♪</i>

217
00:20:23.138 --> 00:20:25.057
<i>♪ Show them I'm worthy ♪</i>

218
00:20:25.140 --> 00:20:28.185
<i>♪ And while I show them ♪</i>

219
00:20:28.268 --> 00:20:32.314
<i>♪ I'll show me ♪</i>

220
00:20:32.397 --> 00:20:37.486
<i>♪ So let them bring on</i>
<i>all their problems ♪</i>

221
00:20:37.569 --> 00:20:41.198
<i>♪ I'll do better than my best ♪</i>

222
00:20:41.281 --> 00:20:44.576
<i>♪ I have confidence</i>
<i>they'll put me to the test ♪</i>

223
00:20:44.660 --> 00:20:48.205
<i>♪ But I'll make them see</i>
<i>I have confidence in me ♪</i>

224
00:20:48.288 --> 00:20:51.833
<i>♪ Somehow I will impress them ♪</i>

225
00:20:51.917 --> 00:20:55.295
<i>♪ I will be firm but kind ♪</i>

226
00:20:55.379 --> 00:20:59.049
<i>♪ And all those children</i>
<i>Heaven bless them ♪</i>

227
00:20:59.132 --> 00:21:02.344
<i>♪ They will look up to me and mind me ♪</i>

228
00:21:02.427 --> 00:21:05.931
<i>♪ With each step I am more certain ♪</i>

229
00:21:06.014 --> 00:21:09.059
<i>♪ Everything will turn out fine ♪</i>

230
00:21:09.142 --> 00:21:12.646
<i>♪ I have confidence</i>
<i>the world can all be mine ♪</i>

231
00:21:12.729 --> 00:21:18.151
<i>♪ They'll have to agree</i>
<i>I have confidence in me ♪</i>

232
00:21:19.653 --> 00:21:22.739
<i>♪ I have confidence in sunshine ♪</i>

233
00:21:22.823 --> 00:21:26.034
<i>♪ I have confidence in rain ♪</i>

234
00:21:26.118 --> 00:21:29.037
<i>♪ I have confidence</i>
<i>that spring will come again ♪</i>

235
00:21:29.121 --> 00:21:32.749
<i>♪ Besides which, you see</i>
<i>I have confidence in me ♪</i>

236
00:21:32.833 --> 00:21:35.711
<i>♪ Strength doesn't lie in numbers ♪</i>

237
00:21:35.794 --> 00:21:39.047
<i>♪ Strength doesn't lie in wealth ♪</i>

238
00:21:39.131 --> 00:21:42.426
<i>♪ Strength lies in nights</i>
<i>of peaceful slumbers ♪</i>

239
00:21:42.509 --> 00:21:45.679
<i>♪ When you wake up, wake up It tells me ♪</i>

240
00:21:45.762 --> 00:21:49.016
<i>♪ All I trust I leave my heart to ♪</i>

241
00:21:49.099 --> 00:21:52.060
<i>♪ All I trust becomes my own ♪</i>

242
00:21:52.144 --> 00:21:57.107
<i>♪ I have confidence in confidence alone ♪</i>

243
00:22:11.371 --> 00:22:12.956
Oh, help.

244
00:22:25.927 --> 00:22:32.684
<i>♪ I have confidence in confidence alone ♪</i>

245
00:22:32.768 --> 00:22:38.315
<i>♪ Besides which, you see</i>
<i>I have confidence ♪</i>

246
00:22:38.398 --> 00:22:43.737
<i>♪ In me ♪</i>

247
00:22:45.280 --> 00:22:47.491
(doorbell rings)

248
00:22:47.574 --> 00:22:49.618
Oh! Whew!

249
00:22:51.036 --> 00:22:53.622
Hello! Here I am.

250
00:22:56.625 --> 00:22:58.627
I'm from the convent.
I'm the new governess, Captain.

251
00:23:00.212 --> 00:23:02.297
And I'm the old butler, fräulein.

252
00:23:03.340 --> 00:23:06.176
Oh. Well, how do you do?

253
00:23:08.762 --> 00:23:10.680
Hmm.

254
00:23:17.687 --> 00:23:20.774
You'll, uh, wait here, please.

255
00:24:31.470 --> 00:24:33.305
(door opens)

256
00:24:47.652 --> 00:24:49.571
In the future, you'll kindly remember

257
00:24:49.654 --> 00:24:51.656
there are certain rooms in this house
which are not to be disturbed.

258
00:24:53.074 --> 00:24:54.993
Yes, Captain, sir.

259
00:25:02.626 --> 00:25:03.960
And why do you stare at me that way?

260
00:25:04.794 --> 00:25:08.173
Well, you don't look at all
like a sea captain, sir.

261
00:25:09.257 --> 00:25:11.384
I'm afraid you don't look
very much like a governess.

262
00:25:12.594 --> 00:25:13.678
Turn around, please.

263
00:25:13.762 --> 00:25:15.096
-What?
-Turn.

264
00:25:18.808 --> 00:25:20.227
Hat off.

265
00:25:21.770 --> 00:25:23.855
(sighs) It's the dress.

266
00:25:23.939 --> 00:25:26.066
You'll have to put on another one
before you meet the children.

267
00:25:26.149 --> 00:25:28.068
But I don't have another one.

268
00:25:28.151 --> 00:25:30.779
When-- When we enter the abbey,
our worldly clothes are given to the poor.

269
00:25:30.862 --> 00:25:32.697
What about this one?

270
00:25:32.781 --> 00:25:35.408
-The poor didn't want this one.
-Hmm.

271
00:25:35.492 --> 00:25:37.786
I would have made myself a new dress,
but there wasn't time.

272
00:25:37.869 --> 00:25:39.371
I can make my own clothes.

273
00:25:40.121 --> 00:25:42.207
Well, I'll see that you
get some material.

274
00:25:43.041 --> 00:25:45.085
Today, if possible.

275
00:25:45.669 --> 00:25:47.837
-Now, Fräulein, um--
-Maria.

276
00:25:47.921 --> 00:25:49.172
Fräulein Maria, I don't know how much

277
00:25:49.256 --> 00:25:50.840
-the mother abbess has told you.
-Not much.

278
00:25:50.924 --> 00:25:53.385
You are the 12th in a long line
of governesses

279
00:25:53.468 --> 00:25:56.346
who have come to look after my children
since their mother died.

280
00:25:56.429 --> 00:25:58.682
I trust that you will be
an improvement on the last one.

281
00:25:58.765 --> 00:26:00.934
She stayed only two hours.

282
00:26:02.185 --> 00:26:04.020
What's wrong with the children, sir?

283
00:26:06.481 --> 00:26:09.609
There's nothing wrong with the children,
only the governesses.

284
00:26:09.693 --> 00:26:10.944
Oh.

285
00:26:11.027 --> 00:26:12.654
They were completely unable
to maintain discipline.

286
00:26:12.737 --> 00:26:14.406
Without it, this house
cannot be properly run.

287
00:26:14.489 --> 00:26:16.908
-You will please remember that, fräulein?
-Yes, sir.

288
00:26:16.992 --> 00:26:19.119
Every morning you will drill
the children in their studies.

289
00:26:19.202 --> 00:26:22.372
I will not permit them to dream away
their summer holidays.

290
00:26:22.455 --> 00:26:25.584
Each afternoon they will march
about the grounds, breathing deeply.

291
00:26:25.667 --> 00:26:27.377
Bedtime is to be strictly observed,
no exceptions.

292
00:26:27.460 --> 00:26:28.753
Excuse me, sir.
When do they play?

293
00:26:28.837 --> 00:26:31.089
You will see to it that they
conduct themselves at all time

294
00:26:31.172 --> 00:26:32.966
with the utmost orderliness and decorum.

295
00:26:33.049 --> 00:26:35.552
-I'm placing you in command.
-Oh, yes, sir!

296
00:26:38.138 --> 00:26:40.098
(whistle blows)

297
00:26:43.852 --> 00:26:45.895
(whistle blows)

298
00:26:45.979 --> 00:26:48.315
(running footsteps)

299
00:27:01.077 --> 00:27:02.537
(whistle blows)

300
00:27:03.288 --> 00:27:06.666
(whistle blows rhythmically)

301
00:27:22.223 --> 00:27:26.227
(whistle continues blowing rhythmically)

302
00:27:33.193 --> 00:27:34.778
(whistle blows twice)

303
00:27:54.255 --> 00:27:55.799
Hup.

304
00:27:56.633 --> 00:28:00.261
Now, this is your new governess,
Fräulein Maria.

305
00:28:02.972 --> 00:28:05.183
As I sound your signals,
you will step forward and give your name.

306
00:28:05.266 --> 00:28:06.935
You, fräulein, will listen carefully.

307
00:28:07.018 --> 00:28:08.937
Learn their signals so you can
call them when you want them.

308
00:28:09.020 --> 00:28:10.563
(blows three times)

309
00:28:10.647 --> 00:28:12.023
-Liesl.
-(whistle blows twice)

310
00:28:12.107 --> 00:28:14.067
-Friedrich.
-(blows three times)

311
00:28:14.150 --> 00:28:15.860
-Louisa.
-(blows once)

312
00:28:15.944 --> 00:28:17.696
-Kurt.
-(blows five times)

313
00:28:17.779 --> 00:28:19.155
-Brigitta.
-(blows four times)

314
00:28:19.239 --> 00:28:21.074
-Marta.
-(blows six times)

315
00:28:22.033 --> 00:28:23.827
(whistle blows louder)

316
00:28:26.705 --> 00:28:28.748
And Gretl. (clears throat)

317
00:28:32.377 --> 00:28:36.256
Now, let's see how well you listened.

318
00:28:36.339 --> 00:28:38.717
Oh, I-I won't need to whistle for them,
Reverend Captain.

319
00:28:38.800 --> 00:28:42.387
I mean, um, I'll use their names.
And such lovely names.

320
00:28:42.470 --> 00:28:44.139
VON TRAPP: Fräulein,
this is a large house.

321
00:28:44.222 --> 00:28:48.435
The grounds are very extensive,
and I will not have anyone shouting.

322
00:28:48.518 --> 00:28:50.687
You will take this, please.
Learn to use it.

323
00:28:50.770 --> 00:28:52.355
The children will help you.

324
00:28:54.607 --> 00:28:58.236
Now, when I want you,
this is what you will hear.

325
00:28:58.319 --> 00:29:01.489
-(sharp whistling)
-Oh, no, sir. I'm sorry, sir.

326
00:29:02.323 --> 00:29:03.825
I could never answer to a whistle.

327
00:29:03.908 --> 00:29:06.077
Whistles are for dogs
and cats and other animals,

328
00:29:06.161 --> 00:29:08.997
but not for children,
and definitely not for me.

329
00:29:09.080 --> 00:29:10.874
It would be too humiliating.

330
00:29:12.834 --> 00:29:18.006
Fräulein, were you this much trouble
at the abbey?

331
00:29:18.089 --> 00:29:21.176
-Oh, much more, sir.
-Hmm.

332
00:29:24.345 --> 00:29:26.222
(whistle blows)

333
00:29:29.893 --> 00:29:32.187
Excuse me, sir.
I don't know your signal.

334
00:29:33.354 --> 00:29:35.273
You may call me Captain.

335
00:29:42.280 --> 00:29:44.365
(children chuckling)

336
00:29:48.077 --> 00:29:49.954
(sighs) At ease.

337
00:29:53.082 --> 00:29:55.168
Well, now that there's just us,

338
00:29:55.251 --> 00:29:58.713
would you please tell me all your names
again and how old you are?

339
00:29:59.464 --> 00:30:03.843
I'm Liesl. I'm 16 years old
and I don't need a governess.

340
00:30:03.927 --> 00:30:07.764
Well, I'm glad you told me, Liesl.
We'll just be good friends.

341
00:30:09.766 --> 00:30:12.936
I'm Friedrich. I'm 14. I'm impossible.

342
00:30:13.019 --> 00:30:15.772
(chuckles) Really?
Who told you that, Friedrich?

343
00:30:15.855 --> 00:30:18.525
Fräulein Josephine,
four governesses ago.

344
00:30:19.526 --> 00:30:21.236
I'm Brigitta.

345
00:30:23.112 --> 00:30:26.115
You, um, didn't tell me
how old you are, Louisa.

346
00:30:27.450 --> 00:30:30.078
I'm Brigitta. She's Louisa.

347
00:30:30.161 --> 00:30:32.872
She's 13 years old, and you're smart.

348
00:30:32.956 --> 00:30:37.001
I'm 10, and I think your dress
is the ugliest one I ever saw.

349
00:30:37.085 --> 00:30:39.379
Brigitta, you shouldn't say that.

350
00:30:39.462 --> 00:30:41.589
Why not? Don't you think it's ugly?

351
00:30:41.673 --> 00:30:44.843
Of course,
but Fräulein Hilda's was ugliest.

352
00:30:45.593 --> 00:30:48.263
I'm Kurt. I'm 11. I'm incorrigible.

353
00:30:48.346 --> 00:30:49.681
Congratulations.

354
00:30:49.764 --> 00:30:51.516
What's "incorrigible"?

355
00:30:51.975 --> 00:30:54.936
I think it means you want
to be treated like a boy.

356
00:30:56.229 --> 00:30:57.647
Mm-hm?

357
00:30:57.730 --> 00:31:01.276
I'm Marta, and I'm gonna
be seven on Tuesday.

358
00:31:01.359 --> 00:31:02.902
And I'd like a pink parasol.

359
00:31:03.987 --> 00:31:05.655
Well, pink's my favorite color, too.

360
00:31:05.738 --> 00:31:09.158
-(stomping)
-Yes, you're Gretl.

361
00:31:09.242 --> 00:31:11.828
And you're five years old?

362
00:31:11.911 --> 00:31:13.538
My, you're practically a lady.

363
00:31:13.621 --> 00:31:15.290
(girls chuckle)

364
00:31:16.374 --> 00:31:19.878
Now I have to tell you a secret--
I've never been a governess before.

365
00:31:20.795 --> 00:31:23.506
You mean you don't know anything
about being a governess?

366
00:31:23.590 --> 00:31:25.675
Nothing. I'll need lots of advice.

367
00:31:25.758 --> 00:31:29.762
Well, the best way to start
is to be sure to tell Father

368
00:31:29.846 --> 00:31:31.180
to mind his own business.

369
00:31:31.264 --> 00:31:33.558
-You must never come to dinner on time.
-Uh--

370
00:31:33.641 --> 00:31:36.019
-Never eat your soup quietly.
-(slurps)

371
00:31:36.102 --> 00:31:38.563
And during dessert,
always blow your nose.

372
00:31:38.646 --> 00:31:41.774
Don't you believe a word they say,
Fräulein Maria.

373
00:31:41.858 --> 00:31:44.068
-Why not?
-Because I like you!

374
00:31:44.152 --> 00:31:45.612
-Yes.
-(clapping)

375
00:31:45.695 --> 00:31:48.948
All right now, children!
Outside for your walk. Father's orders.

376
00:31:49.032 --> 00:31:51.618
Now, hurry up, hurry up.
Quick, quick, quick, quick, quick!

377
00:31:51.701 --> 00:31:53.286
-Uh, Fräulein Maria.
-Mmm.

378
00:31:53.369 --> 00:31:55.496
-I'm Frau Schmidt, the housekeeper.
-How do you do?

379
00:31:55.580 --> 00:31:58.333
How do you do?
I'll show you to your room. Follow me.

380
00:32:09.510 --> 00:32:11.512
MARIA: Poor little dears.

381
00:32:15.308 --> 00:32:18.144
(gasps, screaming)

382
00:32:23.566 --> 00:32:26.361
-Oh!
-You're very lucky.

383
00:32:26.444 --> 00:32:29.238
-With Fräulein Helga, it was a snake.
-(exhales)

384
00:32:42.543 --> 00:32:44.128
Good evening.

385
00:32:45.463 --> 00:32:49.425
-Good evening, children.
-ALL: Good evening, Fräulein Maria.

386
00:32:49.509 --> 00:32:51.761
(screams, laughing)

387
00:32:55.348 --> 00:32:57.976
-(groans)
-Enchanting little ritual.

388
00:32:58.059 --> 00:33:01.270
Something you, um,
learned at the abbey?

389
00:33:02.230 --> 00:33:05.358
No, um, it's, um... um...

390
00:33:05.441 --> 00:33:07.694
-(patting)
-...rheumatism.

391
00:33:12.865 --> 00:33:14.117
Hmm.

392
00:33:17.286 --> 00:33:19.372
Excuse me, Captain.
Haven't we forgotten to thank the Lord?

393
00:33:28.548 --> 00:33:31.801
For what we are about to receive,
may the Lord make us truly thankful. Amen.

394
00:33:31.884 --> 00:33:34.345
-Amen.
-CHILDREN: Amen.

395
00:33:38.516 --> 00:33:41.144
I'd like to thank each and every
one of you for the precious gift

396
00:33:41.227 --> 00:33:43.479
you left in my pocket earlier today.

397
00:33:45.815 --> 00:33:48.568
Um, what gift?

398
00:33:51.738 --> 00:33:54.490
It's meant to be a secret, Captain,
between the children and me.

399
00:33:54.574 --> 00:33:57.535
Uh-huh. Then I suggest that
you keep it and let us eat.

400
00:33:58.453 --> 00:34:00.747
Knowing how nervous
I must have been,

401
00:34:00.830 --> 00:34:03.374
a stranger in a new household,

402
00:34:03.458 --> 00:34:06.002
knowing how important it was
for me to feel accepted,

403
00:34:06.085 --> 00:34:08.880
it was so kind and thoughtful of you

404
00:34:08.963 --> 00:34:14.719
to make my first moments
here so warm and happy and pleasant.

405
00:34:20.099 --> 00:34:21.934
(cries)

406
00:34:24.896 --> 00:34:26.981
-What is the matter, Marta?
-Nothing.

407
00:34:30.693 --> 00:34:33.029
(children crying)

408
00:34:39.118 --> 00:34:44.248
Fräulein, is it to be at every meal,
or merely at, uh, dinnertime,

409
00:34:44.332 --> 00:34:46.834
that you intend leading us all
through this rare

410
00:34:46.918 --> 00:34:49.879
and wonderful new world of indigestion?

411
00:34:52.548 --> 00:34:54.258
Oh, they're all right, Captain.
They're just happy.

412
00:34:54.342 --> 00:34:56.552
(crying louder)

413
00:35:06.187 --> 00:35:07.980
(doorbell rings)

414
00:35:13.820 --> 00:35:16.906
-Herr Rolfe, good evening.
-Good evening, Franz.

415
00:35:16.989 --> 00:35:19.534
-I trust everything is under control?
-Yes. Yes.

416
00:35:19.617 --> 00:35:21.536
Good.

417
00:35:21.619 --> 00:35:23.955
-Are there, uh, any developments?
-Perhaps.

418
00:35:24.038 --> 00:35:26.124
-Is the captain at home?
-He's at dinner.

419
00:35:26.207 --> 00:35:28.918
-With the family?
-Yes.

420
00:35:29.001 --> 00:35:30.920
Please give him this telegram at once.

421
00:35:31.003 --> 00:35:32.839
Certainly.

422
00:35:44.684 --> 00:35:46.435
-A telegram for you, sir.
-Mmm.

423
00:35:48.646 --> 00:35:50.940
Franz, who delivered it?

424
00:35:51.023 --> 00:35:53.025
That young lad, Rolfe, of course.

425
00:35:55.653 --> 00:35:59.448
-Father, may I be excused?
-Hmm. Children.

426
00:35:59.532 --> 00:36:02.702
In the morning,
I shall be going to Vienna.

427
00:36:02.785 --> 00:36:05.079
ALL: Not again, Father!

428
00:36:09.041 --> 00:36:11.377
How long will you be gone
this time, Father?

429
00:36:11.460 --> 00:36:13.546
I'm not sure, Gretl. Not sure.

430
00:36:13.629 --> 00:36:15.256
LOUISA: To visit Baroness
Schraeder again?

431
00:36:15.339 --> 00:36:17.341
Mind your own business!

432
00:36:17.425 --> 00:36:20.303
As a matter of fact, yes, Louisa.

433
00:36:21.179 --> 00:36:23.639
Why can't we ever get
to see the baroness?

434
00:36:23.723 --> 00:36:26.142
KURT: Why would she want to see you?

435
00:36:26.225 --> 00:36:28.477
It just so happens, Marta,
that you<i> are </i>going to see the baroness.

436
00:36:28.561 --> 00:36:30.354
I'm bringing her back with me
to visit us all.

437
00:36:31.105 --> 00:36:32.398
CHILDREN: Good!

438
00:36:32.481 --> 00:36:34.609
And Uncle Max.

439
00:36:34.692 --> 00:36:37.486
-Uncle Max!
-Uncle Max!

440
00:36:52.543 --> 00:36:53.544
Rolfe!

441
00:36:57.006 --> 00:36:58.549
Oh, Rolfe.

442
00:37:00.968 --> 00:37:02.553
No, Liesl, we mustn't.

443
00:37:02.637 --> 00:37:05.264
-Why not, silly?
-I don't know. It's just--

444
00:37:05.348 --> 00:37:07.058
Isn't this why you're here waiting for me?

445
00:37:07.141 --> 00:37:10.353
Yes, of course.
I've missed you, Liesl.

446
00:37:10.436 --> 00:37:12.146
You have? How much?

447
00:37:12.230 --> 00:37:14.565
So much that I even
thought of sending you a telegram

448
00:37:14.649 --> 00:37:16.234
just so I'd be able to deliver it here.

449
00:37:16.317 --> 00:37:20.112
Oh, that's a lovely thought.
Why don't you, right now?

450
00:37:20.196 --> 00:37:21.697
But I'm here.

451
00:37:21.781 --> 00:37:24.867
Please, Rolfe, send me a telegram.

452
00:37:24.951 --> 00:37:27.411
I'll start it for you. Dear Liesl...

453
00:37:28.704 --> 00:37:30.748
Dear Liesl.

454
00:37:30.831 --> 00:37:34.126
I'd like to be able to tell you
how I feel about you. Stop.

455
00:37:34.877 --> 00:37:39.590
Unfortunately, this wire
is already too expensive.

456
00:37:39.674 --> 00:37:42.677
-Sincerely, Rolfe.
-"Sincerely"?

457
00:37:42.760 --> 00:37:45.346
-Cordially.
-"Cordially"?

458
00:37:45.429 --> 00:37:47.640
Affectionately?

459
00:37:47.723 --> 00:37:49.392
Mmm!

460
00:37:49.475 --> 00:37:51.394
Will there be any reply?

461
00:37:53.145 --> 00:37:55.147
Dear Rolfe. Stop.

462
00:37:56.274 --> 00:37:58.859
Don't stop. Your Liesl.

463
00:38:00.444 --> 00:38:04.782
If only we didn't always have to wait
for someone to send Father a telegram.

464
00:38:04.865 --> 00:38:06.993
How do I know when I'll see you again?

465
00:38:08.452 --> 00:38:09.662
Well, let's see.

466
00:38:12.456 --> 00:38:14.458
I could come here by mistake...

467
00:38:15.376 --> 00:38:17.420
with a telegram for Colonel Schneider.

468
00:38:17.503 --> 00:38:19.297
He's here from Berlin, staying with--

469
00:38:21.173 --> 00:38:22.967
No one's supposed
to know he's here.

470
00:38:23.050 --> 00:38:25.428
-Don't tell your father, now.
-Why not?

471
00:38:25.511 --> 00:38:29.348
-Well, your father's so... so Austrian.
-We're all Austrian.

472
00:38:29.432 --> 00:38:31.434
Well, some people think
we ought to be German,

473
00:38:31.517 --> 00:38:34.020
and they're very mad
at those who don't think so.

474
00:38:34.103 --> 00:38:35.730
They're getting ready to--

475
00:38:37.690 --> 00:38:40.067
Well, let's hope your father
doesn't get into trouble.

476
00:38:40.151 --> 00:38:42.945
Don't worry about Father.
He's a big naval hero.

477
00:38:43.029 --> 00:38:45.239
-He was even decorated by the emperor.
-I know.

478
00:38:45.323 --> 00:38:48.701
I don't worry about him,
but I do worry about his daughter.

479
00:38:48.784 --> 00:38:50.578
Me? Why?

480
00:38:50.661 --> 00:38:52.580
-Well, you're so--
-What?

481
00:38:52.663 --> 00:38:54.498
Well, you're such a baby!

482
00:38:54.582 --> 00:38:57.752
I'm 16. What's such a baby about that?

483
00:39:00.212 --> 00:39:03.883
<i>♪ You wait, little girl</i>
<i>on an empty stage ♪</i>

484
00:39:03.966 --> 00:39:07.845
<i>♪ For fate to turn the light on ♪</i>

485
00:39:07.928 --> 00:39:11.057
<i>♪ Your life, little girl</i>
<i>is an empty page ♪</i>

486
00:39:11.140 --> 00:39:15.853
<i>♪ That men will want to write on ♪</i>

487
00:39:15.936 --> 00:39:20.691
<i>♪ To write on ♪</i>

488
00:39:22.401 --> 00:39:26.322
<i>♪ You are sixteen going on seventeen ♪</i>

489
00:39:26.405 --> 00:39:30.242
<i>♪ Baby, it's time to think ♪</i>

490
00:39:30.326 --> 00:39:34.330
<i>♪ Better beware</i>
<i>Be canny and careful ♪</i>

491
00:39:34.413 --> 00:39:38.584
<i>♪ Baby, you're on the brink ♪</i>

492
00:39:38.667 --> 00:39:42.505
<i>♪ You are sixteen going on seventeen ♪</i>

493
00:39:42.588 --> 00:39:46.175
<i>♪ Fellows will fall in line ♪</i>

494
00:39:46.258 --> 00:39:50.262
<i>♪ Eager young lads</i>
<i>and roues and cads ♪</i>

495
00:39:50.346 --> 00:39:54.225
<i>♪ Will offer you food and wine ♪</i>

496
00:39:54.308 --> 00:39:58.521
<i>♪ Totally unprepared are you ♪</i>

497
00:39:58.604 --> 00:40:02.358
<i>♪ To face a world of men ♪</i>

498
00:40:02.441 --> 00:40:06.362
<i>♪ Timid and shy and scared are you ♪</i>

499
00:40:06.445 --> 00:40:10.866
<i>♪ Of things beyond your ken ♪</i>

500
00:40:10.950 --> 00:40:14.662
<i>♪ You need someone older and wiser ♪</i>

501
00:40:14.745 --> 00:40:18.916
<i>♪ Telling you what to do ♪</i>

502
00:40:18.999 --> 00:40:22.461
<i>♪ I am seventeen going on eighteen ♪</i>

503
00:40:22.545 --> 00:40:28.801
<i>♪ I'll take care of you ♪</i>

504
00:40:34.849 --> 00:40:37.977
(thunder rumbling)

505
00:40:50.614 --> 00:40:52.700
(thunderclap)

506
00:41:01.292 --> 00:41:04.795
<i>♪ I am sixteen going on seventeen ♪</i>

507
00:41:04.879 --> 00:41:08.632
<i>♪ I know that I'm naive ♪</i>

508
00:41:08.716 --> 00:41:11.927
<i>♪ Fellows I meet may tell me I'm sweet ♪</i>

509
00:41:12.011 --> 00:41:15.681
<i>♪ And willingly I believe ♪</i>

510
00:41:15.764 --> 00:41:19.435
<i>♪ I am sixteen going on seventeen ♪</i>

511
00:41:19.518 --> 00:41:22.897
<i>♪ Innocent as a rose ♪</i>

512
00:41:22.980 --> 00:41:25.024
<i>♪ Bachelor dandies ♪</i>

513
00:41:25.107 --> 00:41:27.109
<i>♪ Drinkers of brandies ♪</i>

514
00:41:27.193 --> 00:41:30.571
<i>♪ What do I know of those ♪</i>

515
00:41:30.654 --> 00:41:34.366
<i>♪ Totally unprepared am I ♪</i>

516
00:41:34.450 --> 00:41:38.287
<i>♪ To face a world of men ♪</i>

517
00:41:38.370 --> 00:41:41.749
<i>♪ Timid and shy and scared am I ♪</i>

518
00:41:41.832 --> 00:41:45.836
<i>♪ Of things beyond my ken ♪</i>

519
00:41:45.920 --> 00:41:49.507
<i>♪ I need someone older and wiser ♪</i>

520
00:41:49.590 --> 00:41:53.302
<i>♪ Telling me what to do ♪</i>

521
00:41:53.385 --> 00:41:57.306
<i>♪ You are seventeen going on eighteen ♪</i>

522
00:41:57.389 --> 00:42:02.937
<i>♪ I'll depend on you ♪</i>

523
00:42:42.560 --> 00:42:46.897
(thunder rumbling)

524
00:43:44.830 --> 00:43:48.459
Whee!

525
00:43:48.542 --> 00:43:52.296
(thunderclaps)

526
00:43:54.506 --> 00:43:57.051
-(knocking)
-Come in.

527
00:43:58.260 --> 00:43:59.845
Frau Schmidt.

528
00:44:02.556 --> 00:44:04.433
For your new dresses, Fräulein Maria.

529
00:44:04.516 --> 00:44:06.435
The captain had these sent out from town.

530
00:44:06.518 --> 00:44:08.562
Oh, how lovely.

531
00:44:08.646 --> 00:44:11.857
Oh, I'm sure these will make
the prettiest clothes I've ever had.

532
00:44:12.900 --> 00:44:15.819
Tell me, do you think the captain would
get me some more material if I asked him?

533
00:44:15.903 --> 00:44:17.988
How many dresses does a governess need?

534
00:44:18.072 --> 00:44:20.240
-(window bangs)
-No, not for me. For the children.

535
00:44:20.324 --> 00:44:22.201
I want to make them some play clothes.

536
00:44:22.284 --> 00:44:25.412
The von Trapp children don't play.
They march.

537
00:44:26.205 --> 00:44:28.332
Surely, you don't approve of that.

538
00:44:30.209 --> 00:44:32.544
Ever since the captain
lost his poor wife, he--

539
00:44:32.628 --> 00:44:35.506
he runs this house as if he were
on one of his ships again.

540
00:44:35.589 --> 00:44:37.716
Whistles, orders.

541
00:44:37.800 --> 00:44:39.760
No more music, no more laughing.

542
00:44:39.843 --> 00:44:42.304
Nothing that reminds him of her.

543
00:44:42.388 --> 00:44:45.224
-Even the children.
-But it's so wrong!

544
00:44:46.100 --> 00:44:48.936
Oh, well. How do you like your room?

545
00:44:49.019 --> 00:44:51.146
-There'll be new drapes at the windows.
-Mmm.

546
00:44:51.230 --> 00:44:52.856
New drapes? But these are fine.

547
00:44:52.940 --> 00:44:55.150
Nevertheless, new ones have been ordered.

548
00:44:55.234 --> 00:44:57.277
Oh, but I really don't need them.

549
00:44:57.361 --> 00:44:59.571
-Good night now.
-Frau Schmidt.

550
00:45:00.614 --> 00:45:02.866
Do you think if I asked the captain
tomorrow about the material--

551
00:45:02.950 --> 00:45:04.910
He's leaving for Vienna
in the morning.

552
00:45:04.993 --> 00:45:07.287
Oh, yes, of course.
Well, how long will he be gone?

553
00:45:07.371 --> 00:45:09.373
That all depends.

554
00:45:09.456 --> 00:45:11.875
The last time he visited the baroness,
he stayed for a month.

555
00:45:11.959 --> 00:45:13.627
Oh.

556
00:45:13.711 --> 00:45:15.921
I shouldn't be saying this-- not to you.

557
00:45:16.004 --> 00:45:18.632
I mean, I don't know you that well.

558
00:45:18.716 --> 00:45:21.510
But if you ask me,
the captain's thinking very seriously

559
00:45:21.593 --> 00:45:23.971
of marrying the woman
before the summer's over.

560
00:45:24.054 --> 00:45:25.597
Oh, that would be wonderful.

561
00:45:25.681 --> 00:45:27.516
Well, the children will
have a mother again.

562
00:45:29.017 --> 00:45:32.187
Yes. Well, good night.

563
00:45:32.271 --> 00:45:36.233
-Good night.
-(thunder rumbling)

564
00:45:46.869 --> 00:45:51.498
-(thunderclap)
-(rain falling)

565
00:45:51.582 --> 00:45:55.210
Dear Father, now I know
why you've sent me here.

566
00:45:55.294 --> 00:45:58.297
To help these children prepare
themselves for a new mother.

567
00:45:58.380 --> 00:46:01.800
And I pray that this will become
a happy family in thy sight.

568
00:46:01.884 --> 00:46:05.220
God bless the captain.
God bless Liesl and Friedrich.

569
00:46:05.304 --> 00:46:09.641
God bless Louisa, Brigitta,
Marta and little Gretl.

570
00:46:09.725 --> 00:46:12.102
And, oh, I forgot the other boy.
What's his name?

571
00:46:12.186 --> 00:46:14.146
(thunder rumbling)

572
00:46:14.229 --> 00:46:16.148
Well, God bless what's-his-name.

573
00:46:16.231 --> 00:46:19.193
God bless the reverend mother
and Sister Margaretta...

574
00:46:20.444 --> 00:46:22.404
...and everybody at Nonnberg Abbey.

575
00:46:22.488 --> 00:46:24.323
And now, dear God, about Liesl--

576
00:46:25.240 --> 00:46:27.075
Help her to know that I'm her friend.

577
00:46:27.159 --> 00:46:29.453
And help her to tell me
what she's been up to.

578
00:46:30.829 --> 00:46:32.623
-Are you going to tell on me?
-Shh.

579
00:46:32.706 --> 00:46:35.834
Help me to be understanding
so that I may guide her footsteps.

580
00:46:35.918 --> 00:46:38.962
In the name of the Father and of the Son
and the Holy Ghost. Amen.

581
00:46:39.046 --> 00:46:42.090
I was out taking a walk, and somebody
locked the doors earlier than usual,

582
00:46:42.174 --> 00:46:43.926
and I didn't want to wake everybody up.

583
00:46:44.009 --> 00:46:46.011
So when I saw your window open--

584
00:46:47.429 --> 00:46:49.598
You're not going to tell Father, are you?

585
00:46:50.682 --> 00:46:51.892
Hmm.

586
00:46:55.979 --> 00:46:57.981
How in the world
did you climb up here?

587
00:46:58.065 --> 00:47:00.984
It's how we always got into this room
to play tricks on the governess.

588
00:47:01.068 --> 00:47:04.738
Louisa can make it with a whole jar of
spiders in her hand.

589
00:47:04.822 --> 00:47:06.532
-(closes window)
-Spiders?

590
00:47:08.242 --> 00:47:10.118
Oh. Liesl.

591
00:47:10.869 --> 00:47:13.038
Were you out walking all by yourself?

592
00:47:20.921 --> 00:47:24.925
You know, if we wash that dress out
tonight, nobody would notice it tomorrow.

593
00:47:25.008 --> 00:47:27.094
You could put this on.

594
00:47:28.887 --> 00:47:32.015
Take your dress in there.
Put it to soak in the bathtub.

595
00:47:32.099 --> 00:47:34.685
Then come back here and sit on the bed,
and we'll have a talk.

596
00:47:37.104 --> 00:47:39.314
I told you today
I didn't need a governess.

597
00:47:40.190 --> 00:47:41.775
Well, maybe I do.

598
00:47:46.780 --> 00:47:49.616
(thunderclap)

599
00:48:06.633 --> 00:48:10.470
(thunderclap)

600
00:48:12.222 --> 00:48:15.100
Gretl? Are you scared?

601
00:48:15.183 --> 00:48:18.478
(thunderclap)

602
00:48:18.562 --> 00:48:21.064
You're not frightened
of a thunderstorm, are you?

603
00:48:21.148 --> 00:48:23.567
You just stay right here with me. Oh!

604
00:48:24.943 --> 00:48:28.155
-Where are the others?
-They're asleep. They're not scared.

605
00:48:28.238 --> 00:48:31.283
(thunderclap)

606
00:48:33.160 --> 00:48:35.245
Oh, no? Look.

607
00:48:36.538 --> 00:48:38.707
All right, everybody.
Up here on the bed.

608
00:48:38.790 --> 00:48:41.209
-BRIGITTA: Really?
-Well, just this once. Come on.

609
00:48:42.002 --> 00:48:44.171
Now, all we have to do
is wait for the boys.

610
00:48:44.254 --> 00:48:46.173
You won't see them.
Boys are brave.

611
00:48:46.256 --> 00:48:48.091
(thunderclap)

612
00:48:52.387 --> 00:48:55.015
Uh, you boys weren't scared too,
were you?

613
00:48:55.098 --> 00:48:58.894
Oh, no. We just wanted
to be sure that you weren't.

614
00:48:59.686 --> 00:49:01.521
That's very thoughtful of you, Friedrich.

615
00:49:01.605 --> 00:49:04.983
It wasn't my idea.
It was Kurt's.

616
00:49:05.067 --> 00:49:07.861
Kurt! That's the one I left out.
God bless Kurt.

617
00:49:07.945 --> 00:49:10.489
(thunderclap)

618
00:49:10.572 --> 00:49:12.199
Why does it do that?

619
00:49:12.282 --> 00:49:15.243
Well, the lightning
says something to the thunder,

620
00:49:15.327 --> 00:49:16.870
and the thunder answers back.

621
00:49:16.954 --> 00:49:19.456
-The lightning must be nasty.
-Not really.

622
00:49:19.539 --> 00:49:21.541
Then why does the thunder
get so angry?

623
00:49:21.625 --> 00:49:23.627
It makes me want to cry.

624
00:49:23.710 --> 00:49:26.004
(thunderclap)

625
00:49:26.088 --> 00:49:28.632
Well, now, when anything bothers me
and I'm feeling unhappy,

626
00:49:28.715 --> 00:49:30.550
I just try and think of nice things.

627
00:49:30.634 --> 00:49:32.427
LOUISA, MARTA:
What kind of things?

628
00:49:32.511 --> 00:49:35.013
Oh! Well, let me see.
Nice things--

629
00:49:35.097 --> 00:49:36.390
Daffodils!

630
00:49:37.265 --> 00:49:39.142
Green meadows.

631
00:49:39.226 --> 00:49:41.770
Skies full of stars.

632
00:49:41.853 --> 00:49:45.399
Raindrops on roses
and whiskers on kittens.

633
00:49:45.482 --> 00:49:48.485
<i>♪ Bright copper kettles</i>
<i>and warm woolen mittens ♪</i>

634
00:49:48.568 --> 00:49:51.738
<i>♪ Brown paper packages</i>
<i>tied up with strings ♪</i>

635
00:49:51.822 --> 00:49:56.118
<i>-♪ These are a few of my favorite things ♪</i>
-(thunderclap)

636
00:49:58.412 --> 00:50:01.456
<i>♪ Cream-colored ponies</i>
<i>and crisp apple strudels ♪</i>

637
00:50:01.540 --> 00:50:04.751
<i>♪ Doorbells and sleigh bells</i>
<i>and schnitzel with noodles ♪</i>

638
00:50:04.835 --> 00:50:08.338
<i>♪ Wild geese that fly</i>
<i>with the moon on their wings ♪</i>

639
00:50:08.422 --> 00:50:11.591
<i>♪ These are a few of my favorite things ♪</i>

640
00:50:11.675 --> 00:50:13.510
(children laughing)

641
00:50:13.593 --> 00:50:16.221
<i>♪ Girls in white dresses</i>
<i>with blue satin sashes ♪</i>

642
00:50:16.304 --> 00:50:19.599
<i>♪ Snowflakes that stay</i>
<i>on my nose and eyelashes ♪</i>

643
00:50:19.683 --> 00:50:22.936
<i>♪ Silver white winters</i>
<i>that melt into springs ♪</i>

644
00:50:23.020 --> 00:50:26.481
<i>♪ These are a few</i>
<i>of my favorite things ♪</i>

645
00:50:26.565 --> 00:50:28.358
<i>♪ When the dog bites ♪</i>

646
00:50:28.442 --> 00:50:30.193
<i>♪ When the bee stings ♪</i>

647
00:50:30.277 --> 00:50:33.113
<i>♪ When I'm feeling sad ♪</i>

648
00:50:33.196 --> 00:50:36.408
<i>-♪ I simply remember my favorite things ♪</i>
-(giggling)

649
00:50:36.491 --> 00:50:38.827
<i>♪ And then I don't feel ♪</i>

650
00:50:38.910 --> 00:50:43.874
<i>♪ So bad ♪</i>

651
00:50:43.957 --> 00:50:46.001
-Does it really work?
-Of course it does. You try it.

652
00:50:46.084 --> 00:50:47.502
What things do you like?

653
00:50:47.586 --> 00:50:49.671
-Pussy willows.
-Christmas!

654
00:50:49.755 --> 00:50:51.965
-Bunny rabbits!
-KURT: Snakes!

655
00:50:52.049 --> 00:50:54.342
-(squealing)
-BRIGITTA: Chocolate icing!

656
00:50:54.426 --> 00:50:56.845
-No school!
-KURT: Pillow fights!

657
00:50:56.928 --> 00:50:59.222
-Telegrams!
-Birthday presents!

658
00:50:59.306 --> 00:51:00.891
-Any presents!
-Yes!

659
00:51:00.974 --> 00:51:02.601
-GRETL: Ladybugs!
-MARTA: Cats!

660
00:51:02.684 --> 00:51:04.269
-KURT: Rats!
-A good sneeze!

661
00:51:04.352 --> 00:51:07.022
-KURT: Ah-choo!
-Gesundheit!

662
00:51:07.105 --> 00:51:08.398
See what fun it is?

663
00:51:08.482 --> 00:51:11.568
<i>♪ Raindrops on roses</i>
<i>and whiskers on kittens ♪</i>

664
00:51:11.651 --> 00:51:13.111
<i>-♪ Bright copper kettles ♪</i>
-(window bangs)

665
00:51:13.195 --> 00:51:14.654
<i>♪ And warm woolen mittens ♪</i>

666
00:51:14.738 --> 00:51:17.699
<i>♪ Brown paper packages</i>
<i>tied up with strings ♪</i>

667
00:51:17.783 --> 00:51:21.078
<i>♪ These are a few</i>
<i>of my favorite things ♪</i>

668
00:51:22.621 --> 00:51:24.206
Oh!

669
00:51:24.289 --> 00:51:27.125
<i>♪ Cream-colored ponies</i>
<i>and crisp apple strudels ♪</i>

670
00:51:27.209 --> 00:51:30.337
<i>♪ Doorbells and sleigh bells</i>
<i>and schnitzel with noodles ♪</i>

671
00:51:30.420 --> 00:51:33.673
<i>♪ Wild geese that fly</i>
<i>with the moon on their wings ♪</i>

672
00:51:33.757 --> 00:51:37.385
<i>♪ These are a few of my favorite things ♪</i>

673
00:51:37.469 --> 00:51:38.929
Oh! Together!

674
00:51:39.888 --> 00:51:42.974
<i>♪ Girls in white dresses</i>
<i>with blue satin sashes ♪</i>

675
00:51:43.058 --> 00:51:45.852
<i>♪ Snowflakes that stay</i>
<i>on my nose and eyelashes ♪</i>

676
00:51:45.936 --> 00:51:49.106
<i>♪ Silver white winters</i>
<i>that melt into springs ♪</i>

677
00:51:49.189 --> 00:51:52.859
<i>♪ These are a few of my favorite things ♪</i>

678
00:51:52.943 --> 00:51:54.861
<i>♪ When the dog bi-- ♪</i>

679
00:51:54.945 --> 00:51:57.948
Dog bites-- We--

680
00:52:04.079 --> 00:52:06.581
-Hello.
-Fräulein, did I not tell you

681
00:52:06.665 --> 00:52:09.543
that bedtime is to be strictly
observed in this house?

682
00:52:09.626 --> 00:52:12.587
Well, the children were upset
by the storm, so I thought that if I--

683
00:52:13.547 --> 00:52:15.006
You did, sir.

684
00:52:15.090 --> 00:52:18.510
And do you or do you not have difficulty
remembering such simple instructions?

685
00:52:20.095 --> 00:52:22.347
Only during thunderstorms, sir.

686
00:52:22.430 --> 00:52:23.723
(giggles)

687
00:52:24.683 --> 00:52:26.351
-Liesl?
-Yes, Father?

688
00:52:26.434 --> 00:52:28.687
I don't recall seeing you
anywhere after dinner.

689
00:52:28.770 --> 00:52:31.189
Oh, really? Well, as a matter of fact--

690
00:52:31.273 --> 00:52:34.609
-Yes?
-Well, I-- I was--

691
