<i>♪ Climb every mountain ♪</i>

1633
01:57:14.527 --> 01:57:18.406
<i>♪ Ford every stream ♪</i>

1634
01:57:18.489 --> 01:57:23.703
<i>♪ Follow every rainbow ♪</i>

1635
01:57:23.786 --> 01:57:28.499
<i>♪ Till you find ♪</i>

1636
01:57:28.583 --> 01:57:34.338
<i>♪ Your dream ♪</i>

1637
01:57:41.137 --> 01:57:44.807
Now, it's not like my children
to be secretive.

1638
01:57:44.891 --> 01:57:47.268
We're not being secretive, Father.

1639
01:57:47.351 --> 01:57:51.814
Mm-hm. And it's not like
my children to be late for dinner.

1640
01:57:51.898 --> 01:57:54.108
-We lost track of the time.
-Ah.

1641
01:57:54.192 --> 01:57:56.194
-CHILDREN: Yes!
-I see.

1642
01:57:56.277 --> 01:57:58.696
Who's going to be the first one
to tell me the truth?

1643
01:57:58.780 --> 01:58:02.200
Friedrich?
Brigitta? Liesl?

1644
01:58:03.367 --> 01:58:04.994
Where do you think we were, Father?

1645
01:58:05.078 --> 01:58:07.246
Hmm? Now--

1646
01:58:12.001 --> 01:58:15.713
Well, if you don't believe us, you must
have some idea where you think we were.

1647
01:58:18.466 --> 01:58:20.635
-(giggling)
-Aha! Marta!

1648
01:58:20.718 --> 01:58:23.179
-MARTA: Yes, Father.
-You tell me.

1649
01:58:24.305 --> 01:58:28.142
Friedrich told you, Father.
We were berry picking.

1650
01:58:28.226 --> 01:58:32.313
I forgot. You were berry picking!

1651
01:58:32.396 --> 01:58:35.066
-CHILDREN: Yeah! Yeah!
-All afternoon?

1652
01:58:35.149 --> 01:58:37.026
-We picked thousands of them.
-Thousands?

1653
01:58:37.110 --> 01:58:40.113
-KURT: I got the most.
-What kind of berries?

1654
01:58:40.196 --> 01:58:43.199
-Uh, blueberries, sir.
-Blueberries! Mmm!

1655
01:58:43.282 --> 01:58:45.535
CHILDREN: Yes! Yes, of course!

1656
01:58:45.618 --> 01:58:48.955
It's, uh, too early for blueberries.

1657
01:58:49.956 --> 01:58:52.416
-They were strawberries.
-Strawberries?

1658
01:58:52.500 --> 01:58:55.419
It's been so cold lately,
they turned blue.

1659
01:58:58.381 --> 01:59:01.259
Aw! (clicking tongue)

1660
01:59:01.342 --> 01:59:03.928
Very well. Show me the berries.

1661
01:59:04.011 --> 01:59:06.597
-BRIGITTA: We--
-LOUISA: Well--

1662
01:59:06.681 --> 01:59:09.267
Show me the berries you picked.
Come on. We don't have them anymore.

1663
01:59:09.350 --> 01:59:11.978
You don't have them anymore?
Well, what happened to them?

1664
01:59:12.061 --> 01:59:14.939
-We-- We--
-We ate them!

1665
01:59:15.022 --> 01:59:16.399
-You ate them?
-Yes!

1666
01:59:16.482 --> 01:59:19.485
-All of them?
-They were delicious!

1667
01:59:19.569 --> 01:59:21.237
Very well.

1668
01:59:21.320 --> 01:59:26.159
Since you've obviously stuffed yourselves
full of thousands of delicious berries...

1669
01:59:26.242 --> 01:59:28.578
-Mmm!
-you can't be hungry anymore, so I'll, uh,

1670
01:59:28.661 --> 01:59:33.082
just have to simply tell Frau Schmidt
to, uh, skip your dinner.

1671
01:59:42.675 --> 01:59:45.511
It's all your fault!
We should have told him the truth.

1672
01:59:45.595 --> 01:59:47.847
And made him boiling mad at us?

1673
01:59:47.930 --> 01:59:50.099
KURT: It's better than starving to death.

1674
01:59:50.183 --> 01:59:53.144
LOUISA: We didn't do anything wrong.
We just wanted to see her.

1675
01:59:54.395 --> 01:59:57.523
My stomach's making noises.

1676
01:59:57.607 --> 02:00:00.818
The least they could have done
was to let us say hello.

1677
02:00:01.611 --> 02:00:03.905
I wonder what grass tastes like.

1678
02:00:03.988 --> 02:00:05.781
I feel awful.

1679
02:00:05.865 --> 02:00:08.367
BRIGITTA: When Fräulein Maria
wanted to feel better,

1680
02:00:08.451 --> 02:00:09.869
she used to sing that song, remember?

1681
02:00:09.952 --> 02:00:12.079
-Yes.
-Let's try it.

1682
02:00:12.914 --> 02:00:19.003
<i>♪ Raindrops on roses</i>
<i>and whiskers on kittens ♪</i>

1683
02:00:20.796 --> 02:00:27.261
<i>♪ Bright copper kettles</i>
<i>and warm woolen mittens ♪</i>

1684
02:00:27.345 --> 02:00:33.684
<i>♪ Brown paper packages</i>
<i>tied up with strings ♪</i>

1685
02:00:33.768 --> 02:00:39.690
<i>♪ These are a few of my favorite things ♪</i>

1686
02:00:39.774 --> 02:00:43.569
Why don't I feel better?

1687
02:00:43.653 --> 02:00:49.158
<i>♪ Girls in white dresses</i>
<i>with blue satin sashes ♪</i>

1688
02:00:49.242 --> 02:00:55.081
(Maria's voice joins in)<i> ♪ Snowflakes</i>
<i>that stay on my nose and eyelashes ♪</i>

1689
02:00:55.164 --> 02:00:57.500
<i>-♪ Silver white winters ♪</i>
-KURT: Fräulein Maria, she's back!

1690
02:00:57.583 --> 02:01:00.127
<i>-♪ That melt into springs ♪</i>
-(all clamoring)

1691
02:01:00.211 --> 02:01:03.339
<i>♪ These are a few of my favorite things ♪</i>

1692
02:01:03.422 --> 02:01:05.341
<i>♪ When the dog bites ♪</i>

1693
02:01:05.424 --> 02:01:07.426
<i>-♪ When the bee stings ♪</i>
-FRIEDRICH: Fräulein Maria!

1694
02:01:07.510 --> 02:01:09.512
<i>♪ When I'm feeling sad ♪</i>

1695
02:01:09.595 --> 02:01:12.848
<i>♪ I simply remember my favorite things ♪</i>

1696
02:01:12.932 --> 02:01:15.810
<i>♪ And then I don't feel ♪</i>

1697
02:01:15.893 --> 02:01:22.441
<i>♪ So bad ♪</i>

1698
02:01:22.525 --> 02:01:25.695
-Oh, children, I'm so glad to see you!
-We missed you!

1699
02:01:25.778 --> 02:01:27.863
Oh, I missed you.
Kurt, how are you?

1700
02:01:27.947 --> 02:01:29.156
Hungry.

1701
02:01:30.908 --> 02:01:32.702
Gretl, what happened to your finger?

1702
02:01:32.785 --> 02:01:34.495
-It got caught.
-Caught in what?

1703
02:01:34.578 --> 02:01:36.038
Friedrich's teeth.

1704
02:01:37.248 --> 02:01:39.458
-Liesl, you all right?
-Just fair.

1705
02:01:39.542 --> 02:01:41.377
Any telegrams been
delivered here lately?

1706
02:01:41.460 --> 02:01:44.338
None at all, fräulein,
but I'm learning to accept it.

1707
02:01:44.422 --> 02:01:47.633
-I'll be glad when school begins.
-Oh, Liesl.

1708
02:01:47.717 --> 02:01:49.552
You can't use school
to escape your problems.

1709
02:01:49.635 --> 02:01:51.220
You have to face them.

1710
02:01:51.304 --> 02:01:52.888
Oh, I have so much to tell you all.

1711
02:01:52.972 --> 02:01:55.224
-We have things to tell you, too.
-I'm sure you do.

1712
02:01:55.308 --> 02:01:58.269
The most important thing is that
Father is going to be married.

1713
02:01:59.478 --> 02:02:00.521
Married?

1714
02:02:00.604 --> 02:02:02.982
Yes, to Baroness Schraeder.

1715
02:02:10.614 --> 02:02:11.741
Oh, I see.

1716
02:02:14.201 --> 02:02:15.619
BRIGITTA: Oh, Father, look!

1717
02:02:15.703 --> 02:02:19.165
FRIEDRICH: Fräulein Maria's
come back from the abbey!

1718
02:02:21.876 --> 02:02:23.169
Good evening, Captain.

1719
02:02:24.545 --> 02:02:26.005
Good evening.

1720
02:02:27.965 --> 02:02:30.551
All right, everyone inside.
Go and get your dinner.

1721
02:02:30.634 --> 02:02:32.386
ALL: Dinner!

1722
02:02:32.470 --> 02:02:35.348
(chattering excitedly)

1723
02:02:41.395 --> 02:02:43.647
You left without saying goodbye.

1724
02:02:44.815 --> 02:02:46.275
Even to the children.

1725
02:02:46.901 --> 02:02:48.819
Well, it was wrong of me.
Forgive me.

1726
02:02:50.654 --> 02:02:52.907
-Why did you?
-Please don't ask me.

1727
02:02:52.990 --> 02:02:54.992
Anyway, the reason no longer exists.

1728
02:02:55.076 --> 02:02:58.662
Fräulein Maria!
You've returned.

1729
02:03:00.414 --> 02:03:02.375
Isn't it wonderful, Georg?

1730
02:03:05.252 --> 02:03:08.798
May I wish you every happiness,
Baroness, and you too, Captain.

1731
02:03:08.881 --> 02:03:10.341
The children tell me you're to be married.

1732
02:03:10.424 --> 02:03:12.176
Thank you, my dear.

1733
02:03:14.595 --> 02:03:17.598
You are back to, uh, stay?

1734
02:03:20.184 --> 02:03:22.895
Only until arrangements can be made
for another governess.

1735
02:04:18.576 --> 02:04:20.327
BARONESS: There you are!

1736
02:04:35.593 --> 02:04:37.845
I really must speak to cook
about the wiener schnitzel.

1737
02:04:37.928 --> 02:04:40.764
It is entirely too delicious
for my figure.

1738
02:04:41.724 --> 02:04:44.393
And it makes you
much too quiet at the dinner table.

1739
02:04:44.477 --> 02:04:46.896
-Hmm.
-Or was it the wine?

1740
02:04:46.979 --> 02:04:49.148
Oh, undoubtedly the wine.

1741
02:04:51.734 --> 02:04:54.236
You have no idea what kind
of trouble I'm having

1742
02:04:54.320 --> 02:04:57.239
trying to decide what to give you
for a wedding present.

1743
02:04:57.323 --> 02:05:00.701
Oh, I know, I'm enough,
but I do want you to have

1744
02:05:00.784 --> 02:05:03.621
some little trifle for the occasion.

1745
02:05:03.704 --> 02:05:07.374
At first, I thought of a fountain pen,
but you've already got one.

1746
02:05:08.626 --> 02:05:11.587
And then I thought perhaps
a villa in the south of France,

1747
02:05:11.670 --> 02:05:13.839
but they are so difficult to gift-wrap.

1748
02:05:14.798 --> 02:05:17.551
Oh, Georg, how do you feel about yachts?

1749
02:05:17.635 --> 02:05:19.762
A long, sleek one
for the Mediterranean,

1750
02:05:19.845 --> 02:05:22.223
or a tiny one
for your bathtub, hmm?

1751
02:05:24.975 --> 02:05:27.311
-Elsa.
-And where to go on our honeymoon?

1752
02:05:27.394 --> 02:05:28.854
Now, that is a real problem.

1753
02:05:28.938 --> 02:05:31.941
I thought a trip around
the world would be lovely.

1754
02:05:32.024 --> 02:05:35.653
Then I said, "Oh, Elsa,
there must be someplace better to go."

1755
02:05:35.736 --> 02:05:37.530
-Don't worry, darling. I--
-Elsa.

1756
02:05:38.447 --> 02:05:40.115
Yes, Georg?

1757
02:05:41.158 --> 02:05:42.451
It's no use...

1758
02:05:43.702 --> 02:05:45.120
...you and I.

1759
02:05:46.455 --> 02:05:49.250
I'm being dishonest to both of us.

1760
02:05:51.293 --> 02:05:52.836
And utterly unfair to you.

1761
02:05:58.175 --> 02:06:00.928
-When two people talk of marriage--
-No, don't.

1762
02:06:01.762 --> 02:06:03.889
Don't say another word, Georg, please.

1763
02:06:06.600 --> 02:06:08.644
You see, um...

1764
02:06:08.727 --> 02:06:11.397
there are other things
I've been thinking of.

1765
02:06:13.023 --> 02:06:15.234
Fond as I am of you,

1766
02:06:15.317 --> 02:06:17.861
I really don't think
you're the right man for me.

1767
02:06:17.945 --> 02:06:21.699
You're, um...
You're much too independent.

1768
02:06:22.575 --> 02:06:27.538
And I-- I need someone
who needs me desperately,

1769
02:06:27.621 --> 02:06:30.791
or at least needs
my money desperately.

1770
02:06:33.294 --> 02:06:35.546
I've enjoyed every moment
we've had together.

1771
02:06:35.629 --> 02:06:37.381
I do thank you for that.

1772
02:06:41.051 --> 02:06:45.097
Now, if, um, you'll forgive me,
I'll go inside, pack my little bags,

1773
02:06:45.180 --> 02:06:47.391
and return to Vienna, where I belong.

1774
02:06:53.397 --> 02:06:57.276
And somewhere out there
is a young lady who I think...

1775
02:06:59.903 --> 02:07:01.322
...will never be a nun.

1776
02:07:13.542 --> 02:07:15.461
Auf Wiedersehen, darling.

1777
02:07:41.445 --> 02:07:42.821
VON TRAPP: Hello.

1778
02:07:48.410 --> 02:07:51.955
I-- I thought I just might find you here.

1779
02:07:55.793 --> 02:07:57.419
Was there--
Was there something you wanted?

1780
02:07:57.503 --> 02:07:59.296
Hmm?

1781
02:07:59.380 --> 02:08:01.048
No, no, no, no.
Sit down. Please.

1782
02:08:03.008 --> 02:08:04.218
Please.

1783
02:08:09.014 --> 02:08:10.849
Uh, may I?

1784
02:08:22.277 --> 02:08:24.321
(chuckles) You know, I was--

1785
02:08:24.405 --> 02:08:27.157
(clears throat) I was thinking, and--
and I was wondering, uh, two things.

1786
02:08:28.826 --> 02:08:32.538
Why did you run away to the abbey?

1787
02:08:33.831 --> 02:08:35.040
And...

1788
02:08:36.208 --> 02:08:38.460
...what was it that made you come back?

1789
02:08:40.295 --> 02:08:42.798
Well, I...
had an obligation to fulfill,

1790
02:08:42.881 --> 02:08:46.427
and I-- I came back to fulfill it.

1791
02:08:46.510 --> 02:08:48.512
Hmm. Is that all?

1792
02:08:50.806 --> 02:08:52.099
And I missed the children.

1793
02:08:53.100 --> 02:08:56.395
Yes. Only the children?

1794
02:08:56.478 --> 02:08:58.564
No. Yes!

1795
02:08:58.647 --> 02:09:00.023
Isn't it right I should have missed them?

1796
02:09:00.107 --> 02:09:02.025
Oh, yes! Yes, of course!

1797
02:09:02.818 --> 02:09:04.820
I was, uh, only hoping that perhaps you...

1798
02:09:06.405 --> 02:09:08.073
perhaps you might, uh...

1799
02:09:09.700 --> 02:09:11.160
Yes?

1800
02:09:12.703 --> 02:09:14.037
Well, uh...

1801
02:09:14.788 --> 02:09:17.291
Nothing was the same
when you were away...

1802
02:09:19.168 --> 02:09:22.212
...and it'll be all wrong again
after you leave.

1803
02:09:22.296 --> 02:09:27.342
And I just thought perhaps
you might, uh, change your mind?

1804
02:09:31.180 --> 02:09:35.225
I'm sure the baroness will
be able to make things fine for you.

1805
02:09:35.768 --> 02:09:37.019
Maria.

1806
02:09:39.146 --> 02:09:40.647
There isn't going to be any baroness.

1807
02:09:41.440 --> 02:09:42.775
There isn't?

1808
02:09:45.110 --> 02:09:47.863
-No.
-I don't understand.

1809
02:09:51.074 --> 02:09:54.995
Well, we've, um, called off
our engagement, you see, and--

1810
02:09:55.078 --> 02:09:56.955
-Oh, I'm sorry.
-Yes.

1811
02:09:57.039 --> 02:09:58.999
-You are?
-Mm-hm.

1812
02:09:59.875 --> 02:10:01.460
-You did?
-Yes.

1813
02:10:03.170 --> 02:10:06.965
Well, you can't marry
someone when you're...

1814
02:10:10.260 --> 02:10:11.929
...in love with someone else.

1815
02:10:15.349 --> 02:10:16.600
Can you?

1816
02:10:52.052 --> 02:10:54.471
(sighs) The Reverend
Mother always says,

1817
02:10:54.555 --> 02:10:57.558
"When the Lord closes a door,
somewhere He opens a window."

1818
02:11:06.191 --> 02:11:08.652
What else does
the Reverend Mother say?

1819
02:11:10.362 --> 02:11:12.155
That you have to look for your life.

1820
02:11:14.157 --> 02:11:16.201
Is that why you came back?

1821
02:11:20.414 --> 02:11:24.209
And have you found it, Maria?

1822
02:11:26.003 --> 02:11:28.005
I think I have.

1823
02:11:31.091 --> 02:11:32.467
I know I have.

1824
02:11:34.761 --> 02:11:36.638
I love you.

1825
02:11:40.601 --> 02:11:42.936
Oh, can this be happening to me?

1826
02:11:45.856 --> 02:11:51.028
<i>♪ Perhaps I had a wicked childhood ♪</i>

1827
02:11:52.779 --> 02:11:57.492
<i>♪ Perhaps I had a miserable youth ♪</i>

1828
02:11:59.286 --> 02:12:06.209
<i>♪ But somewhere</i>
<i>in my wicked, miserable past ♪</i>

1829
02:12:06.293 --> 02:12:11.465
<i>♪ There must have been a moment of truth ♪</i>

1830
02:12:13.050 --> 02:12:14.843
<i>♪ For here you are ♪</i>

1831
02:12:14.927 --> 02:12:16.762
<i>♪ Standing there ♪</i>

1832
02:12:16.845 --> 02:12:20.474
<i>♪ Loving me ♪</i>

1833
02:12:20.557 --> 02:12:23.352
<i>♪ Whether or not ♪</i>

1834
02:12:23.435 --> 02:12:27.022
<i>♪ You should ♪</i>

1835
