<i>♪ A flibbertigibbet</i>
<i>a will-o'-the-wisp, a clown ♪</i>

1879
02:17:18.021 --> 02:17:22.901
<i>♪ Many a thing you know</i>
<i>you'd like to tell her ♪</i>

1880
02:17:22.984 --> 02:17:27.656
<i>♪ Many a thing</i>
<i>she ought to understand ♪</i>

1881
02:17:27.739 --> 02:17:32.202
<i>♪ But how do you make her stay</i>
<i>and listen to all you say ♪</i>

1882
02:17:32.285 --> 02:17:36.414
<i>♪ How do you keep</i>
<i>a wave upon the sand ♪</i>

1883
02:17:36.498 --> 02:17:41.920
<i>♪ Oh, how do you solve</i>
<i>a problem like Maria ♪</i>

1884
02:17:42.003 --> 02:17:48.927
<i>♪ How do you hold</i>
<i>a moonbeam in your hand ♪</i>

1885
02:18:40.812 --> 02:18:43.481
(bells tolling)

1886
02:18:52.240 --> 02:18:54.826
(bell tolls)

1887
02:19:12.135 --> 02:19:15.722
(continues tolling)

1888
02:19:30.779 --> 02:19:35.742
(stringed instruments playing)

1889
02:19:54.594 --> 02:19:56.054
ZELLER: Herr Detweiler!

1890
02:19:59.057 --> 02:20:01.768
-Heil Hitler.
-Oh. Good afternoon, Herr Zeller.

1891
02:20:01.851 --> 02:20:05.313
Perhaps you've not heard.
I'm now the gauleiter.

1892
02:20:05.397 --> 02:20:08.942
-Heil Hitler.
-Oh, uh, heil Hitler.

1893
02:20:09.025 --> 02:20:11.736
I have just come from the house
of Captain von Trapp,

1894
02:20:11.820 --> 02:20:13.988
incidentally, the only one
in the neighborhood

1895
02:20:14.072 --> 02:20:17.033
not flying the flag of the Third Reich
since the Anschluss.

1896
02:20:17.117 --> 02:20:19.702
-But we have dealt with that situation.
-I don't think--

1897
02:20:19.786 --> 02:20:22.288
The housekeeper told me
that I would find you here.

1898
02:20:22.372 --> 02:20:24.833
It was the only information
the woman would give me.

1899
02:20:24.916 --> 02:20:27.043
What kind of information
are you looking for?

1900
02:20:27.961 --> 02:20:30.004
We want to know when
the captain will be returning.

1901
02:20:30.088 --> 02:20:32.132
Well, he's, uh, on his honeymoon trip.

1902
02:20:32.215 --> 02:20:34.384
Uh, he's not been in touch with us.

1903
02:20:34.467 --> 02:20:36.052
Are you asking me to believe
that the captain

1904
02:20:36.136 --> 02:20:38.930
has not communicated
with his children in over a month?

1905
02:20:39.013 --> 02:20:41.808
Herr Zeller,
how many men do you know

1906
02:20:41.891 --> 02:20:44.602
who communicate with their children
while on their honeymoon?

1907
02:20:46.146 --> 02:20:47.772
When he does return,
he will be expected

1908
02:20:47.856 --> 02:20:50.358
to fill his proper position
in the new order.

1909
02:20:50.442 --> 02:20:52.735
Naturally, naturally.
And may I congratulate you--

1910
02:20:52.819 --> 02:20:56.072
that is, your people--
on deciding to allow the festival

1911
02:20:56.156 --> 02:20:57.449
to go on tonight as planned?

1912
02:20:57.532 --> 02:21:01.619
Why should it not go on?
Nothing in Austria has changed.

1913
02:21:01.703 --> 02:21:04.873
Singing and music
will show this to the world.

1914
02:21:04.956 --> 02:21:06.958
Austria is the same.

1915
02:21:07.041 --> 02:21:08.877
Heil Hitler.

1916
02:21:11.129 --> 02:21:13.923
Heil Hitler. (sniffs)

1917
02:21:14.007 --> 02:21:16.009
Come on, children, let's go home.

1918
02:21:16.092 --> 02:21:17.594
Why was he so cross?

1919
02:21:17.677 --> 02:21:19.679
Everybody's cross these days, darling.

1920
02:21:19.762 --> 02:21:23.057
MARTA: Maybe the flag with the black
spider on it makes people nervous.

1921
02:21:23.141 --> 02:21:26.311
-Is Father going to be in trouble?
-He doesn't have to be.

1922
02:21:26.394 --> 02:21:29.314
The thing to do these days
is to get along with everybody.

1923
02:21:29.397 --> 02:21:31.733
I want you all to remember that
tonight at the concert.

1924
02:21:31.816 --> 02:21:34.611
Are we really going to sing before
a whole lot of people tonight?

1925
02:21:34.694 --> 02:21:36.863
Of course.
Look, "The von Trapp Family Singers."

1926
02:21:36.946 --> 02:21:38.907
And here are your names--
Liesl, Friedrich,

1927
02:21:38.990 --> 02:21:41.826
Louisa, Brigitta,
Kurt, Marta and Gretl.

1928
02:21:41.910 --> 02:21:43.912
Why am I always last?

1929
02:21:43.995 --> 02:21:46.831
-Because you are the most important.
-Oh!

1930
02:21:46.915 --> 02:21:48.666
There we go.

1931
02:21:54.589 --> 02:21:58.343
BRIGITTA: Uncle Max, are you sure Father
will approve of our singing in public?

1932
02:21:58.426 --> 02:22:01.137
Oh, he'll be pleased and proud.

1933
02:22:01.221 --> 02:22:03.806
-Liesl, do you think so?
-Don't you trust me?

1934
02:22:03.890 --> 02:22:06.518
-BRIGITTA: No!
-You're a very intelligent girl.

1935
02:22:06.601 --> 02:22:09.562
-(chuckles)
-ROLFE: Liesl! Liesl!

1936
02:22:10.855 --> 02:22:12.190
Rolfe!

1937
02:22:12.857 --> 02:22:15.276
Rolfe, I'm so glad to see you.
It's been such--

1938
02:22:15.360 --> 02:22:17.737
Good afternoon.
You will take this, please,

1939
02:22:17.820 --> 02:22:19.739
and deliver it to your father
as soon as he comes home.

1940
02:22:19.822 --> 02:22:21.866
-He's on his honeymoon.
-I know that.

1941
02:22:21.950 --> 02:22:23.034
You do?

1942
02:22:23.117 --> 02:22:25.828
We make it our business to know
everything about everyone.

1943
02:22:25.912 --> 02:22:28.706
-Who's we?
-See that he gets it.

1944
02:22:28.790 --> 02:22:31.626
-What is it?
-It's a telegram from Berlin.

1945
02:22:31.709 --> 02:22:35.004
Don't you want to come over tonight
and deliver it yourself?

1946
02:22:35.088 --> 02:22:37.882
I am now occupied
with more important matters,

1947
02:22:37.966 --> 02:22:40.760
and your father better be, too,
if he knows what's good for him.

1948
02:22:40.843 --> 02:22:42.679
But, Rolfe--

1949
02:22:58.903 --> 02:23:01.531
CHILDREN: Father! Father!

1950
02:23:01.614 --> 02:23:03.449
Father! Father!

1951
02:23:03.533 --> 02:23:06.911
Father! Father!

1952
02:23:06.995 --> 02:23:09.247
-We didn't expect you so soon.
-Hello, hello, hello!

1953
02:23:09.330 --> 02:23:10.999
When did you get back?

1954
02:23:11.082 --> 02:23:13.084
We didn't expect you home
until next week.

1955
02:23:13.167 --> 02:23:15.753
KURT: Did you bring us
any souvenirs from Paris?

1956
02:23:15.837 --> 02:23:18.965
MARIA: Hello! How are you?

1957
02:23:19.048 --> 02:23:21.384
FRIEDRICH: Why didn't you telephone us?

1958
02:23:21.467 --> 02:23:23.428
Well, we tried to,
but we couldn't get through.

1959
02:23:23.511 --> 02:23:25.888
I had nothing to do with that, Georg.

1960
02:23:25.972 --> 02:23:28.016
We came back as fast as we could.

1961
02:23:28.099 --> 02:23:31.561
Well, well, well, well, well!
We missed you!

1962
02:23:31.644 --> 02:23:33.438
We missed kissing you good night.

1963
02:23:33.521 --> 02:23:36.566
We missed all the noise you make in the
morning telling each other to be quiet.

1964
02:23:36.649 --> 02:23:39.652
-Mostly, we missed hearing you sing.
-Oh, you came back just in time.

1965
02:23:40.737 --> 02:23:44.490
-Look, Fräulein Maria-- I mean, Mother.
-(all laughing)

1966
02:23:44.574 --> 02:23:46.576
We're going to sing
in the festival tonight.

1967
02:23:46.659 --> 02:23:49.537
-What?
-(all chattering)

1968
02:23:52.290 --> 02:23:55.168
(chuckling) Surprise, surprise!

1969
02:23:56.044 --> 02:23:58.546
All right, surprises
for you on the terrace.

1970
02:23:58.630 --> 02:24:01.591
(all chattering)

1971
02:24:01.674 --> 02:24:04.677
-We'll talk about this inside.
-Georg, I would have told you,

1972
02:24:04.761 --> 02:24:06.971
but you were away.
I had to make a last-minute decision.

1973
02:24:08.181 --> 02:24:10.600
-I was fortunate to enter them at all.
-Max.

1974
02:24:10.683 --> 02:24:12.685
-They'll be the talk of the festival.
-Max.

1975
02:24:12.769 --> 02:24:15.480
Imagine, seven children in one family.

1976
02:24:15.563 --> 02:24:17.857
Max!

1977
02:24:17.940 --> 02:24:20.777
Somehow I recall having made it
quite clear to you

1978
02:24:20.860 --> 02:24:23.780
how I feel about my family
singing in public.

1979
02:24:23.863 --> 02:24:25.907
But the committee heard them.
They were enchanted.

1980
02:24:25.990 --> 02:24:29.077
-Max, what did they say?
-I have never heard such enthusiasm.

1981
02:24:29.160 --> 02:24:31.496
Oh, darling, don't you think--
just this once?

1982
02:24:31.579 --> 02:24:33.790
Absolutely out of the question.

1983
02:24:33.873 --> 02:24:36.042
Georg, this is for Austria.

1984
02:24:36.125 --> 02:24:39.587
For Austria?
(scoffs) There is no Austria!

1985
02:24:39.671 --> 02:24:41.756
But the Anschluss happened peacefully.

1986
02:24:41.839 --> 02:24:44.967
-Let's at least be grateful for that.
-Grateful?

1987
02:24:46.886 --> 02:24:48.304
You know, Max...

1988
02:24:49.972 --> 02:24:53.309
...sometimes I don't believe I know you.

1989
02:24:55.520 --> 02:24:59.107
Father, I forgot. This is for you.

1990
02:25:03.736 --> 02:25:08.074
(door opens, closes)

1991
02:25:09.075 --> 02:25:13.079
Maria, he has got to at least pretend
to work with these people.

1992
02:25:13.162 --> 02:25:15.248
You must convince him.

1993
02:25:15.331 --> 02:25:18.418
Max, I can't ask him
to be less than he is.

1994
02:25:18.501 --> 02:25:19.794
Then I'll talk to him.

1995
02:25:19.877 --> 02:25:21.713
If the children don't sing
at the festival, well,

1996
02:25:21.796 --> 02:25:24.424
it will be a reflection on Austria.

1997
02:25:24.507 --> 02:25:27.760
(sighs) Oh, I know.
It wouldn't do me any good either.

1998
02:25:33.182 --> 02:25:35.184
-Mother?
-Hmm?

1999
02:25:35.268 --> 02:25:37.729
That sounds so nice.
I like calling you Mother.

2000
02:25:37.812 --> 02:25:39.522
I like hearing it.

2001
02:25:39.605 --> 02:25:41.190
You love Father very much.

2002
02:25:41.274 --> 02:25:44.068
-I can tell you do.
-Very much.

2003
02:25:44.152 --> 02:25:47.822
Mother, what do you do when
you think you love someone--

2004
02:25:47.905 --> 02:25:51.617
I mean, when you stop
loving someone,

2005
02:25:51.701 --> 02:25:53.870
or he stops loving you?

2006
02:25:55.955 --> 02:25:57.790
Well, you cry a little.

2007
02:25:59.000 --> 02:26:02.920
And then you wait for the sun to come out.
It always does.

2008
02:26:03.004 --> 02:26:06.424
There are so many things I think
I should know, but I don't.

2009
02:26:06.507 --> 02:26:08.718
-I really don't.
-How can you?

2010
02:26:08.801 --> 02:26:11.137
Sometimes I feel the world
is coming to an end.

2011
02:26:11.220 --> 02:26:13.556
And then you feel
it's just beginning?

2012
02:26:13.639 --> 02:26:15.975
-Yes.
-It was that way with me, Liesl.

2013
02:26:16.058 --> 02:26:19.103
And for you, it will be
just as wonderful, I promise.

2014
02:26:19.187 --> 02:26:21.647
Do you really think so?

2015
02:26:21.731 --> 02:26:26.694
<i>♪ When you're sixteen going on seventeen ♪</i>

2016
02:26:26.778 --> 02:26:30.323
<i>♪ Waiting for life to start ♪</i>

2017
02:26:30.406 --> 02:26:35.119
<i>♪ Somebody kind who touches your mind ♪</i>

2018
02:26:35.203 --> 02:26:39.791
<i>♪ Will suddenly touch your heart ♪</i>

2019
02:26:39.874 --> 02:26:41.501
<i>♪ When that happens ♪</i>

2020
02:26:41.584 --> 02:26:43.961
<i>♪ After it happens ♪</i>

2021
02:26:44.045 --> 02:26:48.090
<i>♪ Nothing is quite the same ♪</i>

2022
02:26:48.174 --> 02:26:52.428
<i>♪ Somehow I know I'll jump up and go ♪</i>

2023
02:26:52.512 --> 02:26:57.183
<i>♪ If ever he calls my name ♪</i>

2024
02:26:57.266 --> 02:27:00.686
<i>♪ Gone are your old ideas of life ♪</i>

2025
02:27:00.770 --> 02:27:05.358
<i>♪ The old ideas grow dim ♪</i>

2026
02:27:05.441 --> 02:27:10.446
<i>♪ Lo and behold, you're someone's wife ♪</i>

2027
02:27:10.530 --> 02:27:17.119
<i>♪ And you belong to him ♪</i>

2028
02:27:17.203 --> 02:27:21.582
<i>♪ You may think this kind of adventure ♪</i>

2029
02:27:21.666 --> 02:27:25.002
<i>♪ Never may come to you ♪</i>

2030
02:27:26.796 --> 02:27:32.343
<i>♪ Darling sixteen going on seventeen ♪</i>

2031
02:27:32.426 --> 02:27:37.098
<i>♪ Wait a year ♪</i>

2032
02:27:37.181 --> 02:27:43.145
<i>-♪ Or two ♪</i>
<i>-♪ I'll wait a year ♪</i>

2033
02:27:43.229 --> 02:27:49.777
<i>♪ Just wait a year ♪</i>

2034
02:27:51.529 --> 02:27:55.116
<i>♪ Or two ♪</i>

2035
02:28:02.540 --> 02:28:03.708
VON TRAPP: Liesl.

2036
02:28:20.558 --> 02:28:24.270
-What is it?
-Berlin.

2037
02:28:24.353 --> 02:28:26.898
They've offered me
a commission in their navy.

2038
02:28:26.981 --> 02:28:29.692
I've been requested to accept immediately

2039
02:28:29.775 --> 02:28:33.237
and report to their naval base
at Bremerhaven tomorrow.

2040
02:28:34.238 --> 02:28:38.326
I knew something like this would happen,
but I didn't think it would be so soon.

2041
02:28:38.409 --> 02:28:41.454
To refuse them would be
fatal for all of us.

2042
02:28:43.080 --> 02:28:46.500
And joining them would be... unthinkable.

2043
02:28:52.757 --> 02:28:54.592
Get the children all together.

2044
02:28:54.675 --> 02:28:56.969
Don't say anything that's going
to make them worry.

2045
02:28:57.053 --> 02:28:58.304
Just get them ready.

2046
02:28:59.305 --> 02:29:01.390
We've got to get out of Austria...

2047
02:29:03.225 --> 02:29:05.394
and this house...

2048
02:29:07.271 --> 02:29:08.731
...tonight.

2049
02:29:13.611 --> 02:29:16.489
(crickets chirping)

2050
02:29:52.775 --> 02:29:55.778
MAX: It strains my back,
it breaks my heart when I think

2051
02:29:55.861 --> 02:29:58.197
of a certain singing group that will
not appear at the festival tonight.

2052
02:29:58.280 --> 02:30:01.158
By the time you've made the announcement,
we'll be over the border.

2053
02:30:01.242 --> 02:30:03.536
I hope you appreciate
the sacrifice I'm making.

2054
02:30:03.619 --> 02:30:05.162
You have no choice.

2055
02:30:05.246 --> 02:30:07.957
(grunts) I know.
That's why I'm making it.

2056
02:30:08.791 --> 02:30:11.585
MARTA: Why doesn't Father
turn the motor on?

2057
02:30:11.669 --> 02:30:13.754
Because he doesn't want
anyone to hear us!

2058
02:30:13.838 --> 02:30:15.047
Shh!

2059
02:30:18.009 --> 02:30:21.387
LOUISA: What will Frau Schmidt and
Franz say when they discover we're gone?

2060
02:30:21.470 --> 02:30:23.055
They'll be able to answer truthfully.

2061
02:30:23.139 --> 02:30:25.099
They didn't know anything
about it if anyone asks them.

2062
02:30:25.182 --> 02:30:27.351
-Will we be coming back here?
-Someday, Liesl.

2063
02:30:27.435 --> 02:30:29.437
I do hope someday.

2064
02:30:29.520 --> 02:30:32.398
GRETL: Are Father and Uncle Max
going to push the car

2065
02:30:32.481 --> 02:30:34.650
-all the way to Switzerland?
-Shh!

2066
02:31:01.135 --> 02:31:03.220
Something wrong with your car, Captain?

2067
02:31:03.304 --> 02:31:05.890
Yes, as a matter of fact,
we couldn't get it started.

2068
02:31:10.102 --> 02:31:11.437
Karl.

2069
02:31:13.522 --> 02:31:16.108
Fix Captain von Trapp's car
so that it will start.

2070
02:31:25.201 --> 02:31:27.953
(car engine starts)

2071
02:31:39.465 --> 02:31:41.383
Excellent, Karl.

2072
02:31:45.054 --> 02:31:48.849
I've not asked you where
you and your family are going.

2073
02:31:48.933 --> 02:31:50.601
Nor have you asked me why I'm here.

2074
02:31:50.684 --> 02:31:54.105
Well, apparently, we're both suffering
from a deplorable lack of curiosity.

2075
02:31:55.523 --> 02:31:58.317
You were sent a telegram,
which you did not answer.

2076
02:31:58.400 --> 02:32:01.654
A telegram from Admiral von Schreiber
of the navy of the Third Reich.

2077
02:32:01.737 --> 02:32:04.865
I was under the impression, Herr Zeller,

2078
02:32:04.949 --> 02:32:08.786
that the contents of telegrams
in Austria are private!

2079
02:32:08.869 --> 02:32:12.790
At least the Austria... I know.

2080
02:32:13.833 --> 02:32:15.584
I have my orders.

2081
02:32:15.668 --> 02:32:18.087
And they are to take you personally
to Bremerhaven tonight

2082
02:32:18.170 --> 02:32:19.505
where you will accept
your commission.

2083
02:32:21.674 --> 02:32:26.846
I'm afraid that's going
to be quite... impossible.

2084
02:32:26.929 --> 02:32:28.973
You see, we, uh--

2085
02:32:29.056 --> 02:32:31.433
uh, all of us--
the entire family--

2086
02:32:31.517 --> 02:32:34.812
will be...
singing in the festival tonight.

2087
02:32:36.021 --> 02:32:38.482
As a matter of fact,
that's where we were going now.

2088
02:32:38.566 --> 02:32:41.152
Couldn't possibly let them down now.

2089
02:32:42.027 --> 02:32:45.156
-I just hope we're not too late.
-Yes.

2090
02:32:45.239 --> 02:32:47.950
And you ask me to believe
that you, Captain von Trapp,

2091
02:32:48.033 --> 02:32:50.035
are singing in a concert?

2092
02:32:50.119 --> 02:32:53.956
Believe me, it will be a performance
beyond anything even I've dreamt of.

2093
02:32:54.874 --> 02:32:56.375
Like you, Herr Zeller,

2094
02:32:56.458 --> 02:32:59.587
I, too, am a man of...
hidden talents.

2095
02:32:59.670 --> 02:33:02.548
MAX: Yes, um-- Here.

2096
02:33:02.631 --> 02:33:04.300
The program.

2097
02:33:09.305 --> 02:33:11.140
It says here only the names
of the children.

2098
02:33:11.807 --> 02:33:14.935
It says "The von Trapp Family Singers,"

2099
02:33:15.019 --> 02:33:18.564
and I'm the head
of the von Trapp family, am I not?

2100
02:33:20.524 --> 02:33:24.653
And these, um-- these travel clothes
that you're all wearing?

2101
02:33:24.737 --> 02:33:26.822
Our costumes, naturally.

2102
02:33:26.906 --> 02:33:29.742
Herr Zeller, this night air is not good
for the children's voices.

2103
02:33:36.790 --> 02:33:39.919
Well, a slight delay in my
orders will not be serious.

2104
02:33:41.545 --> 02:33:45.090
Therefore, you will sing.

2105
02:33:46.467 --> 02:33:48.510
You will all sing,

2106
02:33:48.594 --> 02:33:50.971
but only because that's
the way I want it to be.

2107
02:33:52.389 --> 02:33:54.975
It will demonstrate that nothing
in Austria has changed.

2108
02:33:55.851 --> 02:33:59.146
And when you
are finished singing,

2109
02:33:59.230 --> 02:34:01.273
you, Captain von Trapp,
will be taken to Bremerhaven.

2110
02:34:03.484 --> 02:34:06.570
Now, if you will all get into your car,

2111
02:34:06.654 --> 02:34:10.324
we will escort The von Trapp
Family Singers to the festival.

2112
02:34:10.407 --> 02:34:13.410
No escort will be necessary, Herr Zeller.

2113
02:34:13.494 --> 02:34:16.205
Necessary?
A pleasure, Captain.

2114
02:34:16.997 --> 02:34:19.750
After all, we would not want you
to get lost in the crowds.

2115
02:34:22.127 --> 02:34:24.755
-Would we?
-No.

2116
02:34:30.386 --> 02:34:31.971
(car engines start)

2117
02:34:41.272 --> 02:34:44.900
<i>-♪ Sew, a needle pulling thread ♪</i>
<i>-♪ A needle pulling thread ♪</i>

2118
02:34:44.984 --> 02:34:48.153
<i>-♪ La, a note to follow sew ♪</i>
<i>-♪ A note to follow sew ♪</i>

2119
02:34:48.237 --> 02:34:50.197
<i>♪ Tea, a drink with jam and bread ♪</i>

2120
02:34:50.281 --> 02:34:52.449
<i>♪ A drink with jam and bread ♪</i>

2121
02:34:52.533 --> 02:34:54.952
<i>-♪ A drink with jam and bread ♪</i>
<i>-♪ A drink with jam and bread ♪</i>

2122
02:34:55.035 --> 02:34:57.037
<i>♪ Jam and bread</i>
<i>With jam and bread ♪</i>

2123
02:34:57.121 --> 02:35:00.291
<i>-♪ Tea with jam and bread ♪</i>
<i>-♪ Tea with jam and bread ♪</i>

2124
02:35:00.374 --> 02:35:02.293
<i>♪ Jam and bread</i>
<i>Jam and bread ♪</i>

2125
02:35:02.376 --> 02:35:05.379
<i>-♪ Tea with jam, jam and bread ♪</i>
<i>-♪ Jam and bread ♪</i>

2126
02:35:05.462 --> 02:35:07.840
<i>♪ Tea with jam</i>
<i>Jam and bread ♪</i>

2127
02:35:13.762 --> 02:35:17.016
-MARIA:<i> ♪ With jam ♪</i>
-CHILDREN:<i> ♪ A-B-C, A-B-C ♪</i>

2128
02:35:17.099 --> 02:35:20.477
<i>-♪ With jam ♪</i>
-CHILDREN:<i> ♪ Do Re Mi Do Re Mi ♪</i>

2129
02:35:20.561 --> 02:35:24.565
ALL:<i> ♪ Tea with jam and bread ♪</i>

2130
02:35:24.648 --> 02:35:27.651
<i>♪ With jam and bread</i>
<i>With jam, with jam ♪</i>

2131
02:35:27.735 --> 02:35:33.365
<i>♪ And bread ♪</i>

2132
02:35:36.702 --> 02:35:39.997
(applause)

2133
02:35:58.640 --> 02:36:00.893
My fellow Austrians...

2134
02:36:03.187 --> 02:36:07.107
I shall not be seeing you again,
perhaps for a very long time.

2135
02:36:08.942 --> 02:36:11.111
I would like to sing for you now...

2136
02:36:12.196 --> 02:36:13.989
...a love song.

2137
02:36:15.741 --> 02:36:17.618
I know you share this love.

2138
02:36:19.370 --> 02:36:22.623
I pray that you will never let it die.

2139
02:36:35.844 --> 02:36:39.306
<i>♪ Edelweiss ♪</i>

2140
02:36:39.390 --> 02:36:42.893
<i>♪ Edelweiss ♪</i>

2141
02:36:42.976 --> 02:36:48.732
<i>♪ Every morning you greet me ♪</i>

2142
02:36:48.816 --> 02:36:52.194
<i>♪ Small and white ♪</i>

2143
02:36:52.277 --> 02:36:55.239
<i>♪ Clean and bright ♪</i>

2144
02:36:55.322 --> 02:37:01.036
<i>♪ You look happy to meet me ♪</i>

2145
02:37:01.120 --> 02:37:03.789
<i>♪ Blossom of snow ♪</i>

2146
02:37:03.872 --> 02:37:07.584
<i>♪ May you bloom and grow ♪</i>

2147
02:37:07.668 --> 02:37:13.257
<i>♪ Bloom and grow forever ♪</i>

2148
02:37:14.842 --> 02:37:17.511
<i>♪ Edelweiss ♪</i>

2149
02:37:17.594 --> 02:37:20.389
<i>♪ Edelweiss ♪</i>

2150
02:37:20.472 --> 02:37:26.562
<i>♪ Bless my homeland forever ♪</i>

2151
02:37:30.941 --> 02:37:34.445
<i>♪ Edelweiss ♪</i>

2152
02:37:34.528 --> 02:37:36.155
<i>♪ Edel-- ♪</i>

2153
02:37:43.328 --> 02:37:46.540
<i>♪ Small and white ♪</i>

2154
02:37:46.623 --> 02:37:49.460
(children join in)
<i>♪ Clean and bright ♪</i>

2155
02:37:49.543 --> 02:37:54.882
<i>♪ You look happy to meet me ♪</i>

2156
02:37:54.965 --> 02:37:57.801
(audience joins in)
<i>♪ Blossom of snow ♪</i>

2157
02:37:57.885 --> 02:38:01.305
<i>♪ May you bloom and grow ♪</i>

2158
02:38:01.388 --> 02:38:07.936
<i>♪ Bloom and grow forever ♪</i>

2159
02:38:08.020 --> 02:38:11.315
<i>♪ Edelweiss ♪</i>

2160
02:38:11.398 --> 02:38:14.318
<i>♪ Edelweiss ♪</i>

2161
02:38:14.401 --> 02:38:17.738
<i>♪ Bless my homeland ♪</i>

2162
02:38:17.821 --> 02:38:24.703
<i>♪ Forever ♪</i>

2163
02:38:40.844 --> 02:38:44.765
I think it'll work.
I shall miss all of you.

2164
02:38:44.848 --> 02:38:47.768
I shall miss the money
I could have made with you.

2165
02:38:50.562 --> 02:38:52.898
Thank you, ladies
and gentlemen, thank you.

2166
02:38:52.981 --> 02:38:56.610
The festival competition
has come to its conclusion,

2167
02:38:56.693 --> 02:38:59.696
except, of course, we don't know
yet what that conclusion will be.

2168
02:38:59.780 --> 02:39:03.534
And while the judges are
arriving at their decision,

2169
02:39:03.617 --> 02:39:06.703
I have been given permission
to offer you an encore.

2170
02:39:06.787 --> 02:39:10.123
This will be the last opportunity
the von Trapps will have

2171
02:39:10.207 --> 02:39:12.584
of singing together
for a long, long time.

2172
02:39:12.668 --> 02:39:17.673
Even now, officials
are waiting in this auditorium

2173
02:39:17.756 --> 02:39:20.676
to escort Captain von Trapp
to his new command

2174
02:39:20.759 --> 02:39:23.595
in the naval forces of the Third Reich.

2175
02:39:23.679 --> 02:39:26.723
(audience murmuring)

2176
02:39:28.850 --> 02:39:32.646
And so, ladies and gentlemen,
the family von Trapp again...

2177
02:39:34.106 --> 02:39:36.650
...to bid you farewell.

2178
02:39:36.733 --> 02:39:38.569
(applause)

2179
02:39:43.699 --> 02:39:47.286
<i>♪ There's a sad sort of clanging</i>
<i>from the clock in the hall ♪</i>

2180
02:39:47.369 --> 02:39:50.998
<i>♪ And the bells in the steeple too ♪</i>

2181
02:39:51.081 --> 02:39:53.417
<i>♪ And up in the nursery ♪</i>

2182
02:39:53.500 --> 02:39:55.544
<i>♪ An absurd little bird ♪</i>

2183
02:39:55.627 --> 02:39:57.963
<i>♪ Is popping out to say cuckoo ♪</i>

2184
02:39:58.046 --> 02:40:01.592
<i>♪ Cuckoo, cuckoo ♪</i>

2185
02:40:01.675 --> 02:40:03.302
<i>-♪ Regretfully they tell us ♪</i>
<i>-♪ Cuckoo ♪</i>

2186
02:40:03.385 --> 02:40:04.970
<i>-♪ But firmly they compel us ♪</i>
<i>-♪ Cuckoo ♪</i>

2187
02:40:05.053 --> 02:40:07.931
<i>♪ To say goodbye ♪</i>

2188
02:40:08.015 --> 02:40:13.520
<i>♪ To you ♪</i>

2189
02:40:16.231 --> 02:40:19.901
<i>♪ So long, farewell</i>
<i>auf Wiedersehen, good night ♪</i>

2190
02:40:19.985 --> 02:40:23.447
<i>♪ We hate to go</i>
<i>and miss this pretty sight ♪</i>

2191
02:40:29.953 --> 02:40:33.749
<i>♪ So long, farewell</i>
<i>auf Wiedersehen, adieu ♪</i>

2192
02:40:33.832 --> 02:40:37.252
<i>♪ Adieu, adieu</i>
<i>to you and you and you ♪</i>

2193
02:40:43.884 --> 02:40:47.679
<i>♪ So long, farewell</i>
<i>auf Wiedersehen, goodbye ♪</i>

2194
02:40:47.763 --> 02:40:50.932
<i>♪ We flit, we float</i>
<i>We fleetly flee, we fly ♪</i>

2195
02:40:57.773 --> 02:41:01.401
<i>♪ So long, farewell</i>
<i>auf Wiedersehen, goodbye ♪</i>

2196
02:41:01.485 --> 02:41:05.197
<i>♪ The sun has gone to bed</i>
<i>and so must I ♪</i>

2197
02:41:05.280 --> 02:41:09.368
<i>♪ Goodbye ♪</i>

2198
02:41:09.451 --> 02:41:14.998
<i>♪ Goodbye ♪</i>

2199
02:41:15.082 --> 02:41:20.629
<i>♪ Goodbye ♪</i>

2200
02:41:20.712 --> 02:41:25.842
<i>♪ Goodbye ♪</i>

2201
02:41:28.887 --> 02:41:33.975
(applauding)

2202
02:41:49.991 --> 02:41:54.287
(audience chattering)

2203
02:41:59.543 --> 02:42:03.922
Ladies and gentlemen, I have here
the decision of our distinguished judges.

2204
02:42:04.005 --> 02:42:06.591
We will start with the award
for third prize.

2205
02:42:06.675 --> 02:42:09.594
For this honor,
the judges have named...

2206
02:42:09.678 --> 02:42:14.224
the first soloist of the choir
of St. Agatha's Church in Murbach--

2207
02:42:14.307 --> 02:42:16.226
Fräulein Schweiger.

2208
02:42:17.018 --> 02:42:22.315
-(fanfare playing)
-(applauding)

2209
02:42:33.869 --> 02:42:36.788
(audience chuckles)

2210
02:42:38.331 --> 02:42:41.293
(audience laughs)

2211
02:42:42.753 --> 02:42:47.090
(applause)

2212
02:42:53.513 --> 02:42:57.768
Second prize to the Toby Reiser Quintet.

2213
02:42:57.851 --> 02:43:01.146
-(fanfare)
-(applauding)

2214
02:43:25.295 --> 02:43:29.925
And the first prize,
the highest honor in all Austria,

2215
02:43:30.008 --> 02:43:32.385
to The von Trapp Family Singers!

2216
02:43:32.469 --> 02:43:35.889
-(fanfare)
-(applauding)

2217
02:43:45.106 --> 02:43:47.317
The Family von Trapp.

2218
02:43:47.400 --> 02:43:50.195
-(fanfare)
-(applauding)

2219
02:44:01.706 --> 02:44:03.041
They're gone!

2220
02:44:08.755 --> 02:44:11.299
(horns honking)

2221
02:44:19.266 --> 02:44:21.434
(doorbell rings)

2222
02:44:21.518 --> 02:44:23.979
MOTHER ABBESS: Come with me.

2223
02:44:24.062 --> 02:44:26.731
(doorbell rings)

2224
02:44:26.815 --> 02:44:31.111
MOTHER ABBESS: Quickly! Quickly!
I have a place you can hide.

2225
02:44:32.362 --> 02:44:35.532
Slowly. Slowly.

2226
02:44:38.159 --> 02:44:40.787
(doorbell rings)

2227
02:44:47.002 --> 02:44:48.879
ZELLER: Open this gate!

2228
02:44:48.962 --> 02:44:50.839
Good evening.

2229
02:44:53.633 --> 02:44:55.218
ZELLER: Hurry up, woman.

2230
02:45:15.196 --> 02:45:18.366
ZELLER: Two men in there!
Six of you, fan out and cover the yard.

2231
02:45:18.450 --> 02:45:20.702
You two, cover the corridor.

2232
02:45:35.091 --> 02:45:37.093
MARIA: Oh, Reverend Mother,
we didn't realize

2233
02:45:37.177 --> 02:45:39.179
we'd put the abbey in this danger.

2234
02:45:39.262 --> 02:45:42.098
No, Maria.
It was right for you to come here.

2235
02:45:42.182 --> 02:45:44.059
We thought we might borrow
your caretaker's car.

2236
02:45:44.142 --> 02:45:46.144
I'm afraid our car
will do you no good now.

2237
02:45:46.227 --> 02:45:48.188
I've been listening to the wireless.

2238
02:45:48.271 --> 02:45:50.357
The borders have just been closed.

2239
02:45:56.571 --> 02:45:58.531
All right, if the borders are closed...

2240
02:46:00.116 --> 02:46:03.078
...then we'll drive up into the hills
and go over those mountains on foot.

2241
02:46:03.954 --> 02:46:06.539
-The children.
-We'll help them. They'll be all right.

2242
02:46:06.623 --> 02:46:08.833
FRIEDRICH: We can do it
without help, Father.

2243
02:46:09.876 --> 02:46:13.588
MOTHER ABBESS: Maria.
You will not be alone.

2244
02:46:13.672 --> 02:46:18.051
Remember, "I will lift up mine eyes unto
the hills from whence cometh my help."

2245
02:46:18.718 --> 02:46:20.053
Yes, Mother.

2246
02:46:21.513 --> 02:46:23.682
-MARTA: I'm scared.
-BRIGITTA: Me, too.

2247
02:46:35.068 --> 02:46:36.569
God be with you.

2248
02:46:43.618 --> 02:46:45.620
-Mother.
-Yes?

2249
02:46:45.704 --> 02:46:48.748
Would it help if we sang
about our favorite things?

2250
02:46:48.832 --> 02:46:51.835
No, darling.
This is one time it would not help.

2251
02:46:51.918 --> 02:46:55.547
You must be very quiet.
Hold tight to me.

2252
02:47:45.013 --> 02:47:47.098
(rattling)

2253
02:47:58.068 --> 02:47:59.903
(rattling)

2254
02:48:09.412 --> 02:48:11.664
(rattling)

2255
02:48:19.047 --> 02:48:21.716
(rattling)

2256
02:48:27.847 --> 02:48:30.517
(rattling)

2257
02:49:10.056 --> 02:49:11.432
LIEUTENANT:
Come on. Let's try the roof.

2258
02:49:22.485 --> 02:49:24.112
(Liesl gasps)

2259
02:50:07.488 --> 02:50:09.824
Rolfe, please.

2260
02:50:14.746 --> 02:50:16.539
VON TRAPP: No, wait!

2261
02:50:26.132 --> 02:50:27.592
Maria.

2262
02:50:28.593 --> 02:50:30.053
Children.

2263
02:50:34.390 --> 02:50:36.726
ROLFE: It's you we want, not them.

